) Mk.I guns]], mount P Mk.I\n*2 \u00d7 [[QF 2 pounder naval gun|QF 2 pdr Mk.II \"pom-pom\" (40 mm L/39)]]\n*6 \u00d7 [[British 21 inch torpedo|21-inch Torpedo Tubes]]\n*''1940 SRE conversion:''\n*3 \u00d7 BL 4.7 in (120mm) Mk.I L/45 guns\n*1 \u00d7 {{convert|3|in|mm|abbr=on}} AA gun\n*2 \u00d7 QF 2 pdr Mk.II \"pom-pom\" (40 mm L/39)\n*3 \u00d7 21-inch Torpedo Tubes (one triple mount)\n*2 \u00d7 [[depth charge]] racks\n*twin [[QF 6 pounder 10 cwt gun]] (1942 \u2013 replaced \u2018A\u2019 gun)\n|Ship motto=\n|Ship nickname=\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship notes=\n|Ship badge=\n}}\n|}\nThe eighth '''HMS ''Worcester'' (D96''', later '''I96)''', was a [[V and W class destroyer|Modified W-class]] [[destroyer]] of the [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Royal Navy]] that saw service in [[World War II]]. She later served as an [[accommodation ship]] as the second '''HMS ''Yeoman'''''.\n\n==Construction and commissioning==\n\n''Worcester'' was ordered in April 1918<ref name=\"navalhistory\"/><ref name=\"uboatnet\"/> as part of the 13th Order of the 1917-1918 Naval Programme. She was [[Keel laying|laid down]] on 20 December 1918 by [[J. Samuel White]] at [[Cowes]], [[Isle of Wight]], and [[Ship naming and launching|launched]] on 24 October 1919.<ref name=\"navalhistory\"/><ref name=\"navalhistorywwi\">[http://www.naval-history.net/WW1NavyBritishShips-Dittmar2.htm Naval History: SHIPS OF THE ROYAL NAVY, 1914-1919 - in ALPHABETICAL ORDER (Part 2 of 2)]</ref> After launching, she was transferred to the [[Royal Navy Dockyard]] at [[Portsmouth]] for [[Fitting-out|fitting out]], and was completed there on 20 September 1922.<ref name=\"navalhistory\"/> She was [[Ship commissioning|commissioned]] into service the same day<ref name=\"uboatnet\"/> with the [[pennant number]] D96.<ref name=\"navalhistorywwi\"/>\n\n==Service history==\n\n===Before World War II===\nAfter entering service with the fleet in 1922, ''Worcester'' saw service in the [[Atlantic Fleet (United Kingdom)|Atlantic Fleet]] and [[Mediterranean Fleet]] before being [[Ship decommissioning|decommissioned]], transferred to the [[Reserve Fleet (United Kingdom)|Reserve Fleet]], and placed in [[Reserve fleet|reserve]] at Portsmouth in the early 1930s.<ref name=\"navalhistory\"/>\n\nIn 1939, ''Worcester'' was selected for recommissioning as the fleet mobilised because of deteriorating diplomatic relations between the United Kingdom and [[Nazi Germany]].<ref name=\"navalhistory\"/>\n\n===World War II===\n\n====1939\u201340====\nAfter the United Kingdom entered [[World War II]] on 3 September 1939, ''Worcester'' prepared for war service, recommissioning that month, taking aboard stores, and reporting for duty with the [[16th Destroyer Flotilla]] &ndash; which also included the [[Flotilla leader|destroyer leader]] {{HMS|Montrose|D01|6}} and the destroyers {{HMS|Venomous|D75|6}}, {{HMS|Veteran|D72|6}}, {{HMS|Verity|D63|6}}, {{HMS|Whitshed|D77|6}}, {{HMS|Wild Swan|D62|6}}, and {{HMS|Wivern|D66|6}} &ndash; at Portsmouth for [[convoy]] escort and patrol operations in the [[English Channel]] and [[Southwestern Approaches]], which she began in October 1939. She remained on these duties until May 1940, when the German [[Battle of France|invasion]] of the [[Netherlands]], [[Belgium]], [[Luxembourg]], and [[France]] began and she came under the [[Commander-in-Chief, Dover]] to support the evacuation of [[Allies of World War II|Allied]] personnel from Europe as German ground forces advanced. On 24 May, she was assigned to [[Operation Dynamo]], the [[Evacuation of Dunkirk|evacuation]] of Allied troops from [[Dunkirk]], France, during which she made six trips to the Dunkirk beaches, transported a total of 4,350 troops to the United Kingdom, and suffered damage in a German air attack on 27 May 1940.<ref name=\"navalhistory\"/>\n\n''Worcester'' was under repair during June 1940 &ndash; the month in which her pennant number was changed to I96 &ndash; but in July 1940 she returned to service with the 16th Destroyer Flotilla, now based at [[Harwich]], for convoy escort and patrol operations in the [[North Sea]]. In August 1940 she was transferred to [[Western Approaches Command]] for convoy defence duty in the [[Western Approaches]], which she continued without major incident through the end of 1940.<ref name=\"navalhistory\"/>\n\n====1941\u201342====\n\nIn January 1941, ''Worcester'' transferred back to the 16th Destroyer Flotilla at Harwich for more North Sea convoy escort and patrol work, this time with ''Whitshed'' and the destroyer leader {{HMS|Mackay|D70|6}} and destroyer {{HMS|Walpole|D41|6}}. In March 1941, she and ''Whitshed'' escorted [[Convoy FS 29]], which was steaming south along the east coast of [[Great Britain]] and came under German air attack on 6 March. On 7 March, she and ''Whitshed'' chased a German [[motor torpedo boat]] &ndash; an S-boat, known to the Allies as an \"[[E-boat]]\" &ndash; which had been detected near the convoy; the two destroyers were unable to make contact with it. Unfortunately for the convoy, the E-boat had been serving as a decoy for the German 1st S-Boote (E-boat) Flotilla, which attacked the convoy when ''Worcester'' and ''Whitshed'' were too far away to intervene. The Germans penetrated the remaining escort &ndash; reduced to only the escort destroyer {{HMS|Pytchley|L92|6}} and the [[sloop-of-war|patrol sloop]] {{HMS|Puffin|L52|6}} &ndash; to sink two of FS 29{{'}}s [[merchant ship]]s.<ref name=\"navalhistory\"/>\n\n''Worcester'' continued her escort and patrol duties without significant incident until February 1942, when her flotilla was put on alert for the possibility that the German [[battlecruiser]]s [[German battlecruiser Scharnhorst|''Scharnhorst'']] and [[German battlecruiser Gneisenau|''Gneisenau'']] and [[heavy cruiser]] [[German cruiser Prinz Eugen|''Prinz Eugen '']] would attempt a breakout from [[Brest, France|Brest]] in German-occupied France to move to a port in Germany. In preparation for opposing such a breakout, ''Worcester'', ''Mackay'', ''Walpole'', and ''Whitshed'' were conducting exercises with the destroyer leader {{HMS|Campbell|D60|6}} and destroyer {{HMS|Vivacious|D36|6}} of the 21st Destroyer Flotilla to practise [[torpedo]] attacks against enemy ships when they received word on 12 February 1942 that the German ships were indeed steaming to Germany via the English Channel, [[Strait of Dover]], and North Sea in what was to become known as the \"[[Channel Dash]].\" The British ships were ordered to attack the German naval force. During her unsuccessful torpedo attack, ''Worcester'' was hit by 11-inch (280-mm) shells from the battlecruisers and 8-inch (203-mm) shells from ''Prinz Eugen'',<ref name=\"navalhistory\" /> suffering 26 killed or mortally wounded and 45 injured. Most of the dead are buried side by side at Shotley Naval Cemetery, opposite Worcester's Harwich moorings <ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.naval-history.net/xDKCas1942-02FEB.htm|title = Casualty Lists of the Royal Navy and Dominion Navies \u2013 February 1942|date = |accessdate = 9 February 2015|website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> The German gunfire inflicted severe structural damage on ''Worcester'', starting fires, flooding her No. 1 [[Boiler room (ship)|boiler room]], and causing her to go dead in the water. Her surviving crew managed to put out her fires, get back underway, and proceed to Parkeston Quay (Harwich) for repairs without the aid of [[Tugboat|tugs]].<ref name=\"navalhistory\"/>\n\nNominated for conversion to a Short-Range Escort, ''Worcester'' was under repair and conversion until August 1942. Returning to service in September 1942, she was assigned to the [[Home Fleet]] at [[Scapa Flow]] in the [[Orkney Islands]] to support [[Arctic convoys of World War II|Arctic convoys]] during their voyages between the United Kingdom and the [[Kola Inlet]] in the [[Soviet Union]]. On 16 September, she deployed with ''Venomous'', the destroyers {{HMS|Amazon|D39|6}}, {{HMS|Bulldog|H91|6}}, {{HMS|Echo|H23|6}} and {{HMS|Windsor|D42|6}}, and the escort destroyer {{HMS|Cowdray|L52|6}} for [[Operation Gearbox]], in which the ships established a refuelling base at [[Lowe Sound]] on [[Spitsbergen]] for Allied escort ships on the Arctic run. With the base established, ''Worcester'' departed Lowe Sound on 20 September with the destroyers {{HMS|Fury|H76|6}} and {{HMS|Impulsive|D11|6}} and the [[Royal Fleet Auxiliary]] [[Oiler (ship)|oiler]] [[RFA Oligarch|RFA ''Oligarch'']] to join [[Convoy QP 14]] during its voyage from the Kola Inlet to [[Loch Ewe]], [[Scotland]]. She detached from QP 14 on 26 September.<ref name=\"navalhistory\"/>\n\n''Worcester'' remained with the Home Fleet through December 1942. That month, she deployed with ''Montrose'' and the destroyers {{HMS|Musketeer|G86|6}} and {{HMS|Raider|H15|6}}, the [[Royal Australian Navy]] destroyer {{HMAS|Queenborough|G70|6}}, and the [[Polish Navy]] destroyer [[ORP Piorun (G65)|ORP ''Piorun'']] as the screen for the [[battleship]]s {{HMS|King George V|41|6}} and {{HMS|Howe|32|6}} and the [[light cruiser]] {{HMS|Bermuda|52|6}} as they provided cover for [[Convoy RA 51]] as it steamed from the Kola Inlet to the United Kingdom in case German heavy warships attempted to interfere in its passage.<ref name=\"navalhistory\"/>\n\n====1943\u201345====\n\nIn January 1943, ''Worcester'' was released from duty with the Home Fleet. She returned to the 16th Destroyer Flotilla at Harwich and in February 1943 resumed operations in the North Sea, escorting convoys and conducting interception patrols targeting German E-boats before they could launch attacks against Allied convoys. On 24 October 1943, she deployed off [[Norfolk]], [[England]], with ''Mackay'' and small craft of the Royal Navy [[Coastal Forces of the Royal Navy|Coastal Forces]] to intercept E-boats thought to be gathering for an attack on Convoys [[Convoy FN 1160|FN 1160]] and [[Convoy FS 1164|FS 1164]], steaming northbound and southbound, respectively, in the North Sea along the east coast of Great Britain. ''Worcester'', ''Mackay'', and the Coastal Forces craft engaged E-boats of the German 4th Torpedo Boat Flotilla on 25 October 1943 off [[Cromer]], preventing them from attacking the convoys; four of the E-boats did not return to base at [[IJmuiden]] in the Netherlands.<ref name=\"navalhistory\"/>\n\n''Worcester'' continued her escort and interception operations until 23 December 1943 when she detonated a [[Naval mine|mine]] in the North Sea near [[Geography of the North Sea|Smith's Knoll]]. The mine destroyed her [[Stern (ship)|stern]] structure, and she was towed to [[Great Yarmouth]]. She was under repair and survey until April 1944, when she was deemed beyond economical repair and was decommissioned.<ref name=\"navalhistory\"/>\n\nIn May 1944, ''Worcester'' was selected for use as an [[accommodation ship]] in [[London]] upon completion of repairs and modification for her new role. In January 1945 she was towed to London, and after local preparation for use as an accommodation ship, was recommissioned with the new name HMS ''Yeoman'', the second Royal Navy ship of the name, in June 1945. She remained in service as such after the [[surrender of Japan]] brought World War II to an end in August 1945.<ref name=\"navalhistory\"/>\n\n==Decommissioning and disposal==\n\n''Yeoman'' remained in use as an accommodation ship until placed on the disposal list in 1946. She was sold for [[Ship breaking|scrapping]] on 17 September 1946 to the [[British Iron & Steel Corporation]] (BISCO), which allocated her to [[Thos W Ward]] to be broken up.<ref name=\"navalhistory\"/><ref name=\"colledge\"/><ref name=\"navalhistorywwi\"/> She was towed to the shipbreaker{{'}}s yard at [[Grays]], [[Essex]], England, in February 1947.<ref name=\"navalhistory\"/><ref name=\"colledge\"/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite journal |last1=Cernuschi |first1=Enrico |last2=Grobmeier |first2=Alvin H. |title=Question 5/98: Damage to British destroyer Campbell |journal=Warship International |date=1999 |volume=XXXVI |issue=2 |pages=194\u2013195 |issn=0043-0374|lastauthoramp=y}}\n*{{cite book|title=Conway's All the World's Fighting Ships 1922\u20131946|editor1-last=Chesneau|editor1-first=Roger|publisher=Conway Maritime Press|location=Greenwich, UK|year=1980|isbn=0-85177-146-7}}\n*{{Colledge}}\n* {{cite book |first1=Maurice |last1=Cocker |first2=Ian |last2=Allan |title=Destroyers of the Royal Navy, 1893\u20131981 |isbn=0-7110-1075-7}}\n* {{cite book|last=Friedman|first=Norman|title=British Destroyers From Earliest Days to the Second World War|publisher=Naval Institute Press|location=Annapolis, Maryland|year=2009|isbn=978-1-59114-081-8}}\n* {{cite book |editor1-last=Gardiner|editor1-first=Robert|editor2-last=Gray|editor2-first=Randal|title=Conway's All the World's Fighting Ships: 1906\u20131921|year=1985|location=Annapolis, Maryland|publisher=Naval Institute Press|isbn=0-85177-245-5|lastauthoramp=y}}\n* {{cite book|last=Lenton|first=H. T.|authorlink=Henry Trevor Lenton|title=British & Empire Warships of the Second World War|publisher=Naval Institute Press|location=Annapolis, Maryland|year=1998|isbn=1-55750-048-7}}\n*{{cite book|last=March|first=Edgar J.|title=British Destroyers: A History of Development, 1892\u20131953; Drawn by Admiralty Permission From Official Records & Returns, Ships' Covers & Building Plans|year=1966|publisher=Seeley Service|location=London |OCLC=164893555}}\n* {{cite book |last=Preston |first=Antony |title='V & W' Class Destroyers 1917\u20131945 |publisher=Macdonald |location=London |year=1971 |oclc=464542895}}\n* {{cite book |last=Raven |first=Alan |last2=Roberts|first2=John  |title='V' and 'W' Class Destroyers |publisher=Arms & Armour |location=London |year=1979 |series=Man o'War |volume=2 |isbn=0-85368-233-X|lastauthoramp=y }}\n* {{cite book|last=Rohwer|first=J\u00fcrgen|title=Chronology of the War at Sea 1939\u20131945: The Naval History of World War Two|publisher=Naval Institute Press|location=Annapolis, Maryland|year=2005|edition=Third Revised|isbn=1-59114-119-2}}\n* {{cite book |last=Whinney |first=Bob |title=The U-boat Peril: A Fight for Survival |publisher=Cassell |year=2000 |isbn=0-304-35132-6 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/uboatperilfightf0000whin }}\n* {{cite book|last=Whitley|first=M. J.|title=Destroyers of World War 2|publisher=Naval Institute Press|date=1988|isbn=0-87021-326-1|location=Annapolis, Maryland}}\n* {{cite book|last=Winser|first=John de D.|title=B.E.F. Ships Before, At and After Dunkirk|publisher=World Ship Society|location=Gravesend, Kent|year=1999|isbn=0-905617-91-6}}\n\n <!-- non-breaking space to keep AWB drones from altering the space before the navbox-->\n{{V and W class destroyer}}\n{{December 1943 shipwrecks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Worcester (D96)}}\n[[Category:V and W-class destroyers of the Royal Navy]]\n[[Category:1919 ships]]\n[[Category:Ships built on the Isle of Wight]]\n[[Category:World War II destroyers of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in December 1943]]\n", "name_user": "Crouch, Swale", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toGrays(link changed toGrays, Essex) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HMS_Worcester_(D96)"}
{"title_page": "Trang Dai massacre", "text_new": "{{short description|1998 mass shooting in Tacoma, WA}}\n{{Orphan|date=December 2014}}\n\nThe '''Trang Dai massacre''' in [[Tacoma, Washington]], occurred on July 5, 1998, when four gunmen entered the Trang Dai Cafe and opened fire, killing five diners and wounding five others. Detectives blamed the violence on warring Asian gangs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20030429&slug=gundealer29 |title=Errant gun dealer, wary agents paved way for Beltway sniper tragedy \u2013 The Seattle Times |publisher=Seattletimes.com |date=2003-04-29 |accessdate=2009-11-10}}</ref>\n\n== Incident ==\nJust after 1:30&nbsp;a.m. on July 5, 1998, three masked gunmen burst into the Trang Dai Cafe and opened fire in the karaoke bar, killing four men and wounding five others. Two other gunmen kept watch out back and killed a waitress as she tried to leave. In all, 41 shots were fired.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19980707&slug=2759875 |title=Family Grieves For Brothers Killed In Tacoma Shooting \u2013 `A Wedding Becomes A Funeral' \u2013 Theories Fly On Reason For Deadly Attack |publisher=Seattletimes.com |date=1998-07-07}}</ref>\nThe five killed were: Nhan Ai Nguyen, 26; Duy Le, 25; his brother, 27-year-old Hai Le; Tuong Hung Do, 33; and waitress Tuyen Vo, 21. Five were injured and eventually recovered from those injuries. Prosecutors claimed the suspects were targeting a patron, who was injured, because of a personal gripe. The crime remains one of Tacoma's worst mass slayings.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.thenewstribune.com/crime/2008/07/05/title_605 |title=The Trang Dai Massarce 10 years later \u2013 The News Tribune |publisher=Thenewstribune.com |date=2008-06-05}}</ref>\n\n== Investigation ==\nOn July 18, 1998, Tacoma police officers conducted a large police operation in which they searched nine homes while looking for eight suspects in the case. Four were arrested during the operation. A fifth was arrested the next day on July 19.\n\nAn [[AK-47]] found at one of the suspects\u2019 homes was traced back to [[Bull's Eye Shooter Supply]]. The same gun shop that was the source of the weapon used in the [[Beltway sniper attacks]].\n\nThe suspected ringleader, 22-year-old Ri Le, killed his younger half-brother, 17-year-old Khanh Trinh, (one of the gunman stationed at the back of the cafe) then himself in a murder-suicide pact as police officers closed in. Another suspect, 18-year-old Samath Mom, committed suicide in jail just a few hours after his arrest. The other five \u2013 Jimmie Chea, Marvin Leo, Veasna Sok, Sarun Truck Ngeth and John Phet \u2013 were convicted and sentenced.\n\n== References ==\n<!--- See [[Wikipedia:Footnotes]] on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal bar|1990s|United States}}\n\n{{coord|47|13|22.3|N|122|26|34.7|W|type:event_region:US_dim:51|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:1998 murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:Attacks on restaurants in North America]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in 1998]]\n[[Category:Murder in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:1998 in Seattle]]\n[[Category:History of Tacoma, Washington]]\n[[Category:1998 mass shootings in the United States]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in the United States]]\n[[Category:Crimes in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Attacks in the United States in 1998]]\n[[Category:July 1998 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Attacks on buildings and structures in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description/test|1998 mass shooting in Tacoma, WA}}\n{{Orphan|date=December 2014}}\n\nThe '''Trang Dai massacre''' in [[Tacoma, Washington]], occurred on July 5, 1998, when four gunmen entered the Trang Dai Cafe and opened fire, killing five diners and wounding five others. Detectives blamed the violence on warring Asian gangs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20030429&slug=gundealer29 |title=Errant gun dealer, wary agents paved way for Beltway sniper tragedy \u2013 The Seattle Times |publisher=Seattletimes.com |date=2003-04-29 |accessdate=2009-11-10}}</ref>\n\n== Incident ==\nJust after 1:30&nbsp;a.m. on July 5, 1998, three masked gunmen burst into the Trang Dai Cafe and opened fire in the karaoke bar, killing four men and wounding five others. Two other gunmen kept watch out back and killed a waitress as she tried to leave. In all, 41 shots were fired.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19980707&slug=2759875 |title=Family Grieves For Brothers Killed In Tacoma Shooting \u2013 `A Wedding Becomes A Funeral' \u2013 Theories Fly On Reason For Deadly Attack |publisher=Seattletimes.com |date=1998-07-07}}</ref>\nThe five killed were: Nhan Ai Nguyen, 26; Duy Le, 25; his brother, 27-year-old Hai Le; Tuong Hung Do, 33; and waitress Tuyen Vo, 21. Five were injured and eventually recovered from those injuries. Prosecutors claimed the suspects were targeting a patron, who was injured, because of a personal gripe. The crime remains one of Tacoma's worst mass slayings.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.thenewstribune.com/crime/2008/07/05/title_605 |title=The Trang Dai Massarce 10 years later \u2013 The News Tribune |publisher=Thenewstribune.com |date=2008-06-05}}</ref>\n\n== Investigation ==\nOn July 18, 1998, Tacoma police officers conducted a large police operation in which they searched nine homes while looking for eight suspects in the case. Four were arrested during the operation. A fifth was arrested the next day on July 19.\n\nAn [[AK-47]] found at one of the suspects\u2019 homes was traced back to [[Bull's Eye Shooter Supply]]. The same gun shop that was the source of the weapon used in the [[Beltway sniper attacks]].\n\nThe suspected ringleader, 22-year-old Ri Le, killed his younger half-brother, 17-year-old Khanh Trinh, (one of the gunman stationed at the back of the cafe) then himself in a murder-suicide pact as police officers closed in. Another suspect, 18-year-old Samath Mom, committed suicide in jail just a few hours after his arrest. The other five \u2013 Jimmie Chea, Marvin Leo, Veasna Sok, Sarun Truck Ngeth and John Phet \u2013 were convicted and sentenced.\n\n== References ==\n<!--- See [[Wikipedia:Footnotes]] on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal bar|1990s|United States}}\n\n{{coord|47|13|22.3|N|122|26|34.7|W|type:event_region:US_dim:51|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:1998 murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:Attacks on restaurants in North America]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in 1998]]\n[[Category:Murder in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:1998 in Seattle]]\n[[Category:History of Tacoma, Washington]]\n[[Category:1998 mass shootings in the United States]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in the United States]]\n[[Category:Crimes in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Attacks in the United States in 1998]]\n[[Category:July 1998 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Attacks on buildings and structures in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Brykeller", "label": "safe", "comment": "removed test tag on short description", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trang_Dai_massacre"}
{"title_page": "South Island robin", "text_new": "{{short description|Passerine species of bird native to New Zealand's South Island}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{speciesbox\n| name = South Island robin\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref =<ref name=IUCN>BirdLife International 2016. Petroica australis. The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species 2016: e.T103734942A93987322. https://doi.org/10.2305/IUCN.UK.2016-3.RLTS.T103734942A93987322.en. Downloaded on 19 August 2019.</ref>\n| image = 070308 Stewart Island robin on Ulva.jpg\n| genus = Petroica\n| species = australis\n| authority = [[Anders Sparrman|Sparrman]], 1788\n}}\n\nThe '''South Island robin''' (''Petroica australis''), is a [[house sparrow|sparrow]]-sized bird found only in [[New Zealand]], where it has the status of a protected endemic species. The birds are sparsely distributed through the [[South Island, New Zealand|South Island]] and [[Stewart Island/Rakiura]], although the distribution is not continuous. The nominate, and the Stewart Island robin (''P. australis rakiura'') are the two [[subspecies]]. The species is closely related to the [[North Island robin]] (formerly ''P. australis longipes'', now considered a distinct species),<ref name=Miller>{{cite journal|last1=Miller|first1=Hilary C.|last2=Lambert|first2=David M.|year=2006|title=A molecular phylogeny of New Zealand's Petroica (Aves: Petroicidae) species based on mitochondrial DNA sequences|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|volume=40|issue=3|pages=844\u2013855|doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2006.04.012|pmid=16750641}}</ref> and also to the extremely rare [[black robin]] (''P. traversi'') of the [[Chatham Islands]].\n\n==Description==\n\nThe South Island robin is a small passerine, 10\u201318&nbsp;cm in length and weighing around 35 g. North Island robins do resemble both females and juveniles of the South Island robins, as well as all the Stewart Island robins, which can sometimes make it difficult to distinguish between the three. The females and juveniles within a particular group of robins look similar to each other, although newly independent juveniles may not yet have the more lightly coloured breast patch.<ref name=PowleslandA>{{cite book|last=Powlesland|first=R. G.|year=1997|title=Protocols for monitoring New Zealand robins: Petroica australis|series=Department of Conservation Technical Series|volume=13|publisher=New Zealand Department of Conservation}}</ref> However, male North Island robins are almost black with a white spot just above the beak, as well as the greyish-white lower breast. Females and juveniles are greyer with more variable pale patches on their breasts and throats. Male South Island robins are dark grey, except for the distinct yellowish-white lower chest, while females and juveniles are again lighter grey with a less distinct breast. Finally, Stewart Island robins look similar to North Island robins (both males and females).<ref name=IUCN/>\n\nNew Zealand robins are relatively long-lived; life-spans of at least 14 years have been recorded in the wild.\n\n==Taxonomy==\n[[File:New Zealand Robin.jpg|thumb|left|South Island robin]]\nThe South Island robin has two subspecies: ''P. australis australis'', the nominate form, and ''P. australis rakiura'', the Stewart Island robin. These subspecies do not overlap in their distributions. The [[North Island robin]] (''P. longipes''), the [[tomtit]] (''Petroica macrocephala''), and the [[black robin]] (''Petroica traversi'') in the Chatham Islands are closely related species. ''P. traversi'' seems to be a Chatham Island derivative of ''P. australis'', although the position of the most recent common ancestor has yet to be determined.<ref name=Miller/> The family [[Petroicidae]] of Australasian robins has a total of 49 species, mostly in Australia, [[New Zealand]], and [[New Guinea]].<ref name=Gill>Gill, F. and D. Donsker, eds. (2020). IOC World Bird List (v 10.1). Doi 10.14344/IOC.ML.10.1.  http://www.worldbirdnames.org/</ref>.\n\n==Fossil record==\nThere is molecular phylogenetic evidence to suggest two waves of immigration by the Petroica genus from Australia. ''P. longipes'' and ''P. australis'' can be traced to the first and ''P. macrocephala'' to the second wave. The evidence suggests that ''P. longipes'' and ''P. australis'' began to diverge prior to the [[Pleistocene]] era, and that the two South Island subspecies of ''P. australis'' began to diverge after the [[Pleistocene]] era. The separation time for the former was about three million years, and only 10,000 years (i.e., postglacial) for the latter. Fossils of New Zealand robins can sometimes be found near pit fall deposits, as they do most of their feeding/foraging on the ground.<ref name=Worthy>{{cite book|last1=Worthy|first1=Trevor H.|last2=Holdaway|first2=Richard N.|year=2002|chapter=Shorebirds, Parrots and Passerines|title=The Lost World of the Moa|pages=410\u2013440}}</ref> The fossil record also indicates the robins' presence throughout lowland New Zealand until drastic habitat reduction through deforestation by the [[Polynesians|Polynesian]] ancestors of the [[M\u0101ori people|M\u0101ori]] and later European colonisers.<ref name=Borkin>{{cite journal|last=Borkin|first=K. M.|last2=Goodman|first2=A. J.|last3=Mayhew|first3=K.|last4=Smith|first4=E.|year=2007|title=South Island robin (Petroica australis australis) abundance and leaf-litter invertebrates in plantation and native forest|journal=Notornis|volume=54|issue=2|pages=65}}</ref>\n\n==Distribution==\n[[File:Petroica australis -Southland District, South Island, New Zealand-8.jpg|thumb|right|South Island robin, [[Southland District]]]]\nHistorically, the South Island robin inhabited much of the lowland of New Zealand's South Island, but its distribution has become much more patchy in the last century due to habitat loss and introduced predation.<ref name=Borkin/>  There are two populations on the east coast of the South Island, and they are slightly more common in the north and west.<ref name=IUCN/> It has fared slightly better than the Stewart Island robin, which has been relegated to 3 subpopulations, all of which are in [[Leptospermum]] swamp scrubland\u2014although this is not their preferred habitat, it is less heavily populated by mammalian predators. Total population was lower than 500 individuals at one point.<ref name=Laws>{{cite journal|last1=Laws|first1=R. J.|last2=Jamieson|first2=I. G.|year=2011|title=Is lack of evidence of inbreeding depression in a threatened New Zealand robin indicative of reduced genetic load?|journal=Animal Conservation|volume=14|issue=1|pages=47\u201355|doi=10.1111/j.1469-1795.2010.00388.x}}</ref> A programme of translocation to predator-free islands (such as [[Ulva Island (New Zealand)|Ulva Island]], Motuara Island, and Nukuwaiata Island) has since been instituted that has been relatively successful at establishing new populations (around 600 individuals on Motuara alone).<ref name=Hale>{{cite journal|last1=Hale|first1=K. A.|last2=Briskie|first2=J. V.|year=2007|title=Decreased immunocompetence in a severely bottlenecked population of an endemic New Zealand bird.|journal=Animal Conservation|volume=10|issue=1|pages=2\u201310|doi=10.1111/j.1469-1795.2006.00059.x}}</ref> In the South Island, ''P. australis'' has a strong affinity for [[Douglas fir]] plantations rather than native forests ([[Kunzea ericoides|kanuka]] trees) or [[Monterey pine]] plantations, apparently due to forest structure rather than strict food availability or viable nesting sites, as the species prefers structurally simple forests with dense, even canopies, and ground covered with leaf litter.<ref name=Borkin/> When the population was introduced to Ulva Island, nesting was positively correlated with presence of broad-leaved coastal vegetation.<ref name=\"ref10\">{{cite journal|last1=Steffens|first1=K. E.|last2=Seddon|first2=P. J.|last3=Mathieu|first3=R.|last4=Jamieson|first4=I. G.|year=2005|title=Habitat selection by South Island saddlebacks and Stewart Island robins reintroduced to Ulva Island|journal=New Zealand Journal of Ecology|volume=2005|pages=221\u2013229}}</ref>\n\n==Behaviour and ecology==\n\n===Breeding===\n\nSouth Island robins are [[Monogamy|genetically monogamous]], and extra-pair paternity is rare. As they do typically remain monogamous, are non-migratory, and remain on their breeding territories year-round, a male and female in one territory will compete for food resources during non-breeding times. Competition is reduced somewhat by slightly different foraging methods; however, they will steal from their mate's cache if given the opportunity.<ref name=Powlesland/> Males do dominate females, and thus will aggressively exclude females from food, such that females will only access food sources when unattended by the males.<ref name=SteerBurns>{{cite journal|last1=Steer|first1=Jamie|last2=Burns|first2=KC|year=2008|title=Seasonal variation in male-female competition, cooperation and selfish hoarding in a monogamous songbird|journal=Behavioral Ecology and Sociobiology|volume=62|issue=7|pages=1175\u20131183|doi=10.1007/s00265-008-0546-z}}</ref> During breeding season, the female is solely responsible for nest building and incubation, and the male will provide the female and the hatchlings with food.<ref name=PowleslandA/>\n\nSouth Island robins become sexually mature between six and 12 months of age. They begin their breeding season fairly early in August or September (Southern Hemisphere spring) and thus can make use of the winter's remaining food stores during this time.<ref name=Powlesland/> They build open-cup nests in tree-forks or inside tree cavities. Incubation lasts 18 days, and chicks leave the nest after 21 days. Five to 25 days after fledglings leave the nest, the pair may breed again. Modal clutch size is two eggs,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Taylor|first1=S. S.|last2=Jamieson|first2=I. G.|last3=Wallis|first3=G. P.|year=2007|title=Historic and contemporary levels of genetic variation in two New Zealand passerines with different histories of decline|journal=Journal of Evolutionary Biology|volume=20|issue=5|pages=2035\u20132047|doi=10.1111/j.1420-9101.2007.01362.x|pmid=17714320}}</ref> with the expected inverse correlation between size and number of eggs.<ref name=PowleslandBolton>{{cite journal|last1=Boulton|first1=Rebecca L|last2=Powlesland|first2=Ralph G.|year=2008|title=Variation in egg size and nest survival with female age in the South Island Robin Petroica australis|journal=Ibis|volume=150|issue=4|pages=824\u2013828|doi=10.1111/j.1474-919x.2008.00853.x}}</ref> Replacement clutches in the case of loss of eggs or nestlings to predation can be produced relatively rapidly, within 3\u201310 days.<ref name=PowleslandA/>\n\n===Feeding===\n[[File:NZ Robin 2008.JPG|thumb|right|Stewart Island robin]]\nInvertebrates, including earthworms, beetles, and other arthropods foraged from the leaf litter comprise most of the South Island robins' diet.<ref name=Worthy/> Invertebrate prey may be [[Hoarding (animal behavior)|cached]] whole or in portions. Single items are cached at separate sites. Prey is typically stored within 10 metres of where it was procured, even if the bird is outside its own territory. In the winter the primary cache is earthworms, while during the summer the trend is toward cicadas. South Island robins have a very good memory of their storage sites; a male was observed to empty as many as five consecutive caches before returning the stores to his mate during incubation.<ref name=Powlesland>{{cite journal|last=Powlesland|first=R. G.|year=1980|title=Food-Storing Behavior of the South Island Robin|journal=Mauri Ora|volume=8|pages=11}}</ref> The birds have demonstrated an ability to differentiate and prioritise caches of varying sizes, up to 12 total items, without any training, which appears to be the highest recorded numerical competency of any wild animal.<ref name=HuntBurns>{{cite journal|last1=Hunt|first1=Simon|last2=Low|first2=Jason|last3=Burns|first3=K.C.|year=2008|title=Adaptive numerical competency in a food-hoarding songbird|journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society of London B: Biological Sciences|volume=275|issue=1649|pages=2373\u20132379|doi=10.1098/rspb.2008.0702|pmc=2603231|pmid=18611847}}</ref> Because of its high metabolic rate, a robin might spend as much as 90% of its day foraging or storing during the winter.<ref name=PowleslandB/> South Island robins have also been observed to eat berries on occasion; however, these are not cached.<ref name=Worthy/>\n\n===Vocalisation===\n[[File:Southislandrobin.jpg|thumb|right|South Island robin]]\nA male's call during non-breeding season is a series of loud notes with descending frequency which start in rapid succession and finish slowly. During breeding season, the males resort to full song to court the females. Full song is a loud, clear, and continuous song which can last for more than 30 minutes with very brief pauses, and is typically sung from the canopy or an [[Rainforest#Emergent layer|emergent]] tree.<ref name=PowleslandA/> Singing also appears to be performed as part of a strategic regulation of body mass. While robins sing during the [[Dawn chorus (birds)|dawn chorus]] as well as throughout the day, they seem to increase their singing according to food availability. When they have had more food, they will increase energetic behaviours such as singing to arrive at a strategic mass by dusk. Thus, even though two robins might begin the day with different weights, they will end the day with similar weights. A side effect of this behaviour might be the showcasing of a particular male's ability to sequester resources: the longer he sings, the more capable he is of finding food, and thus a better candidate for a mate.<ref name=Barnett>{{cite journal|last1=Barnett|first1=Craig A.|last2=Briskie|first2=James V.|year=2011|title=Strategic Regulation of Body Mass and Singing Behavior in New Zealand Robins|journal=Ethology|volume=117|issue=1|pages=28\u201336|doi=10.1111/j.1439-0310.2010.01844.x}}</ref>\n\n==Conservation==\n\nThe South Island robin is listed as being of [[least concern]] on the [[IUCN Red List]].<ref name=IUCN/> However, the Stewart Island robin (''Petroica australis rakiura'') has gone through a couple of bottlenecked populations recently because of deforestation and habitat loss, as well as introduced predators, such as rats, stoats, and feral cats.<ref name=Hale></ref> Because of this sharp decline in the Stewart Island population, several attempts have been made to translocate the Stewart Island robin to other islands nearby where introduced predators do not exist or have been eradicated (see [[South Island robin#Distribution|above]]. However, many of these translocations have involved 12 or fewer colonising individuals, making inbreeding nearly unavoidable. This has led to some apparent immunocompetency issues as well as reproduction problems. On Motuara Island high rates of hatching failure as well as fewer clutches were observed.<ref name=Hale/> Inbreeding and its genetic and immunological consequences therefore remain a concern with this subspecies.\n\nIn contrast, birds in the South Island do not show much genetic loss in comparison with historical populations, although their distribution on the island has become increasingly fragmented.<ref name=Taylor>{{cite journal|last1=Taylor|first1=S. S.|last2=Boessenkool|first2=S.|last3=Jamieson|first3=I. G.|year=2008|title=Genetic monogamy in two long\u2010lived New Zealand passerines|journal=Journal of Avian Biology|volume=39|issue=5|pages=579\u2013583|doi=10.1111/j.0908-8857.2008.04331.x}}</ref>\n\n==South Island robins and 1080 poison==\n\nA number of robin deaths have been recorded as a result of accidental [[sodium fluoroacetate|1080]] poisoning following pest control operations.<ref name=spurr>{{cite book|last=Spurr|first=E.|year=2000|chapter=Impacts of possum control on non-target species|editor=T.L. Montague|title=The brushtail possum: biology, impact and management of an introduced marsupial|publisher=Manaaki Whenua Press|location=Lincoln}}</ref> Most of these were associated with four specific operations in the 1980s that used poor-quality carrot baits.<ref name=\"pce\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pce.parliament.nz/publications/all-publications/evaluating-the-use-of-1080-predators-poisons-and-silent-forests/|title=Evaluating the use of 1080: Predators, poisons and silent forests|date=June 2011|publisher=Parliamentary Commissioner for the Environment|accessdate=7 June 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110614233345/http://www.pce.parliament.nz/publications/all-publications/evaluating-the-use-of-1080-predators-poisons-and-silent-forests|archivedate=14 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> These instances aside, robins have generally responded well to pest control programmes using aerial 1080 operations, with increased chick and adult survival, and increases in population size.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Powlesland|first1=R. G.|last2=Knegtmans|first2=J. W.|last3=Marshall|first3=I. S. J.|year=1999|title=Costs and benefits of aerial 1080 possum control operations using carrot baits to North Island robins (Petroica australis longipes), Pureora Forest Park|journal=New Zealand Journal of Ecology|volume=1999|pages=149\u2013159|url=http://www.lincoln.ac.nz/PageFiles/7074/3474_Powleslandetal__s10663.pdf}}</ref> A 2012 scientific study of a [[Bird ringing|marked]] population by the [[University of Otago]] during a contemporary 1080 poison operation using cereal baits showed no negative impact on robins and suggested a likely population increase by reducing predation pressure from introduced mammals.<ref name=\"TVNZ One News\">{{cite news |url=http://tvnz.co.nz/national-news/study-finds-1080-has-positive-effect-bird-population-video-4844337 |title=Study finds 1080 has positive effect on bird population |author=TVNZ |date=22 April 2012 |work=[[TVNZ]] |accessdate=26 April 2012}}</ref><!-- DEAD LINK Schadewinkel et al. |title=The effect of aerial application of 1080 cereal baits for possum control on South Island robin (Petroica australis) in the Silver Peaks, Dunedin'|url=http://tbfree.org.nz/Portals/0/Research/1080%20-%20robin%20report_final-revised.pdf -->\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.doc.govt.nz/conservation/native-animals/birds/land-birds/nz-robin-toutouwai/ New Zealand Robin] on [[Department of Conservation (New Zealand)|Department of Conservation]] website\n* [http://www.nzbirds.com/birds/toutouwai.html Factsheet on toutouwai, the New Zealand robin] at NZBirds.com\n* [http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/1966/robin/1/ Information about New Zealand robins] on [[Te Ara: The Encyclopedia of New Zealand|Te Ara]]\n* [http://www.doc.org.nz/upload/documents/science-and-technical/docts13.pdf Protocols for monitoring New Zealand robins(Petroica australis)] - [[Department of Conservation (New Zealand)|Department of Conservation]] Technical Series No. 13\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bwLBfaX4VjE/ Video footage of New Zealand robins] on the [[Animal Health Board (New Zealand)|Animal Health Board]] YouTube Channel\n\n{{Petroicidae}}\n{{Birds of New Zealand}}\n{{Portal bar|Birds|New Zealand}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1051396}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:robin, South Island}}\n[[Category:Petroica|South Island robin]]\n[[Category:Birds of the South Island]]\n[[Category:Endemic fauna of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1788|South Island robin]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Anders Sparrman]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Passerine species of bird native to New Zealand's South Island}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{speciesbox\n| name = South Island robin\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref =<ref name=IUCN>BirdLife International 2016. Petroica australis. The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species 2016: e.T103734942A93987322. https://doi.org/10.2305/IUCN.UK.2016-3.RLTS.T103734942A93987322.en. Downloaded on 19 August 2019.</ref>\n| image = 070308 Stewart Island robin on Ulva.jpg\n| genus = Petroica\n| species = australis\n| authority = [[Anders Sparrman|Sparrman]], 1788\n}}\n\nThe '''South Island robin''' (''Petroica australis''), is a [[house sparrow|sparrow]]-sized bird found only in [[New Zealand]], where it has the status of a protected endemic species. The birds are sparsely distributed through the [[South Island, New Zealand|South Island]] and [[Stewart Island/Rakiura]], although the distribution is not continuous. The nominate, and the Stewart Island robin (''P. australis rakiura'') are the two [[subspecies]]. The species is closely related to the [[North Island robin]] (formerly ''P. australis longipes'', now considered a distinct species),<ref name=Miller>{{cite journal|last1=Miller|first1=Hilary C.|last2=Lambert|first2=David M.|year=2006|title=A molecular phylogeny of New Zealand's Petroica (Aves: Petroicidae) species based on mitochondrial DNA sequences|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|volume=40|issue=3|pages=844\u2013855|doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2006.04.012|pmid=16750641}}</ref> and also to the extremely rare [[black robin]] (''P. traversi'') of the [[Chatham Islands]].\n\n==Description==\n\nThe South Island robin is a small passerine, 10\u201318&nbsp;cm in length and weighing around 35 g. North Island robins do resemble both females and juveniles of the South Island robins, as well as all the Stewart Island robins, which can sometimes make it difficult to distinguish between the three. The females and juveniles within a particular group of robins look similar to each other, although newly independent juveniles may not yet have the more lightly coloured breast patch.<ref name=PowleslandA>{{cite book|last=Powlesland|first=R. G.|year=1997|title=Protocols for monitoring New Zealand robins: Petroica australis|series=Department of Conservation Technical Series|volume=13|publisher=New Zealand Department of Conservation}}</ref> However, male North Island robins are almost black with a white spot just above the beak, as well as the greyish-white lower breast. Females and juveniles are greyer with more variable pale patches on their breasts and throats. Male South Island robins are dark grey, except for the distinct yellowish-white lower chest, while females and juveniles are again lighter grey with a less distinct breast. Finally, Stewart Island robins look similar to North Island robins (both males and females).<ref name=IUCN/>\n\nNew Zealand robins are relatively long-lived; life-spans of at least 14 years have been recorded in the wild.\n\n==Taxonomy==\n[[File:New Zealand Robin.jpg|thumb|left|South Island robin]]\nThe South Island robin has two subspecies: ''P. australis australis'', the nominate form, and ''P. australis rakiura'', the Stewart Island robin. These subspecies do not overlap in their distributions. The [[North Island robin]] (''P. longipes''), the [[tomtit]] (''Petroica macrocephala''), and the [[black robin]] (''Petroica traversi'') in the Chatham Islands are closely related species. ''P. traversi'' seems to be a Chatham Island derivative of ''P. australis'', although the position of the most recent common ancestor has yet to be determined.<ref name=Miller/> The family [[Petroicidae]] of Australasian robins has a total of 49 species, mostly in Australia, [[New Zealand]], and [[New Guinea]].<ref name=Gill>Gill, F. and D. Donsker, eds. (2020). IOC World Bird List (v 10.1). Doi 10.14344/IOC.ML.10.1.  http://www.worldbirdnames.org/</ref>.\n\n==Fossil record==\nThere is molecular phylogenetic evidence to suggest two waves of immigration by the Petroica genus from Australia. ''P. longipes'' and ''P. australis'' can be traced to the first and ''P. macrocephala'' to the second wave. The evidence suggests that ''P. longipes'' and ''P. australis'' began to diverge prior to the [[Pleistocene]] era, and that the two South Island subspecies of ''P. australis'' began to diverge after the [[Pleistocene]] era. The separation time for the former was about three million years, and only 10,000 years (i.e., postglacial) for the latter. Fossils of New Zealand robins can sometimes be found near pit fall deposits, as they do most of their feeding/foraging on the ground.<ref name=Worthy>{{cite book|last1=Worthy|first1=Trevor H.|last2=Holdaway|first2=Richard N.|year=2002|chapter=Shorebirds, Parrots and Passerines|title=The Lost World of the Moa|pages=410\u2013440}}</ref> The fossil record also indicates the robins' presence throughout lowland New Zealand until drastic habitat reduction through deforestation by the [[Polynesians|Polynesian]] ancestors of the [[M\u0101ori people|M\u0101ori]] and later European colonisers.<ref name=Borkin>{{cite journal|last=Borkin|first=K. M.|last2=Goodman|first2=A. J.|last3=Mayhew|first3=K.|last4=Smith|first4=E.|year=2007|title=South Island robin (Petroica australis australis) abundance and leaf-litter invertebrates in plantation and native forest|journal=Notornis|volume=54|issue=2|pages=65}}</ref>\n\n==Distribution==\n[[File:Petroica australis -Southland District, South Island, New Zealand-8.jpg|thumb|right|South Island robin, [[Southland District]]]]\nHistorically, the South Island robin inhabited much of the lowland of New Zealand's South Island, but its distribution has become much more patchy in the last century due to habitat loss and introduced predation.<ref name=Borkin/>  There are two populations on the east coast of the South Island, and they are slightly more common in the north and west.<ref name=IUCN/> It has fared slightly better than the Stewart Island robin, which has been relegated to 3 subpopulations, all of which are in [[Leptospermum]] swamp scrubland\u2014although this is not their preferred habitat, it is less heavily populated by mammalian predators. Total population was lower than 500 individuals at one point.<ref name=\"ref7\">{{cite journal|last1=Laws|first1=R. J.|last2=Jamieson|first2=I. G.|year=2011|title=Is lack of evidence of inbreeding depression in a threatened New Zealand robin indicative of reduced genetic load?|journal=Animal Conservation|volume=14|issue=1|pages=47\u201355|doi=10.1111/j.1469-1795.2010.00388.x}}</ref> A programme of translocation to predator-free islands (such as [[Ulva Island (New Zealand)|Ulva Island]], Motuara Island, and Nukuwaiata Island) has since been instituted that has been relatively successful at establishing new populations (around 600 individuals on Motuara alone).<ref name=Hale>{{cite journal|last1=Hale|first1=K. A.|last2=Briskie|first2=J. V.|year=2007|title=Decreased immunocompetence in a severely bottlenecked population of an endemic New Zealand bird.|journal=Animal Conservation|volume=10|issue=1|pages=2\u201310|doi=10.1111/j.1469-1795.2006.00059.x}}</ref> In the South Island, ''P. australis'' has a strong affinity for [[Douglas fir]] plantations rather than native forests ([[Kunzea ericoides|kanuka]] trees) or [[Monterey pine]] plantations, apparently due to forest structure rather than strict food availability or viable nesting sites, as the species prefers structurally simple forests with dense, even canopies, and ground covered with leaf litter.<ref name=Borkin/> When the population was introduced to Ulva Island, nesting was positively correlated with presence of broad-leaved coastal vegetation.<ref name=\"ref10\">{{cite journal|last1=Steffens|first1=K. E.|last2=Seddon|first2=P. J.|last3=Mathieu|first3=R.|last4=Jamieson|first4=I. G.|year=2005|title=Habitat selection by South Island saddlebacks and Stewart Island robins reintroduced to Ulva Island|journal=New Zealand Journal of Ecology|volume=2005|pages=221\u2013229}}</ref>\n\n==Behaviour and ecology==\n\n===Breeding===\n\nSouth Island robins are [[Monogamy|genetically monogamous]], and extra-pair paternity is rare. As they do typically remain monogamous, are non-migratory, and remain on their breeding territories year-round, a male and female in one territory will compete for food resources during non-breeding times. Competition is reduced somewhat by slightly different foraging methods; however, they will steal from their mate's cache if given the opportunity.<ref name=Powlesland/> Males do dominate females, and thus will aggressively exclude females from food, such that females will only access food sources when unattended by the males.<ref name=SteerBurns>{{cite journal|last1=Steer|first1=Jamie|last2=Burns|first2=KC|year=2008|title=Seasonal variation in male-female competition, cooperation and selfish hoarding in a monogamous songbird|journal=Behavioral Ecology and Sociobiology|volume=62|issue=7|pages=1175\u20131183|doi=10.1007/s00265-008-0546-z}}</ref> During breeding season, the female is solely responsible for nest building and incubation, and the male will provide the female and the hatchlings with food.<ref name=PowleslandA/>\n\nSouth Island robins become sexually mature between six and 12 months of age. They begin their breeding season fairly early in August or September (Southern Hemisphere spring) and thus can make use of the winter's remaining food stores during this time.<ref name=Powlesland/> They build open-cup nests in tree-forks or inside tree cavities. Incubation lasts 18 days, and chicks leave the nest after 21 days. Five to 25 days after fledglings leave the nest, the pair may breed again. Modal clutch size is two eggs,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Taylor|first1=S. S.|last2=Jamieson|first2=I. G.|last3=Wallis|first3=G. P.|year=2007|title=Historic and contemporary levels of genetic variation in two New Zealand passerines with different histories of decline|journal=Journal of Evolutionary Biology|volume=20|issue=5|pages=2035\u20132047|doi=10.1111/j.1420-9101.2007.01362.x|pmid=17714320}}</ref> with the expected inverse correlation between size and number of eggs.<ref name=PowleslandBolton>{{cite journal|last1=Boulton|first1=Rebecca L|last2=Powlesland|first2=Ralph G.|year=2008|title=Variation in egg size and nest survival with female age in the South Island Robin Petroica australis|journal=Ibis|volume=150|issue=4|pages=824\u2013828|doi=10.1111/j.1474-919x.2008.00853.x}}</ref> Replacement clutches in the case of loss of eggs or nestlings to predation can be produced relatively rapidly, within 3\u201310 days.<ref name=PowleslandA/>\n\n===Feeding===\n[[File:NZ Robin 2008.JPG|thumb|right|Stewart Island robin]]\nInvertebrates, including earthworms, beetles, and other arthropods foraged from the leaf litter comprise most of the South Island robins' diet.<ref name=Worthy/> Invertebrate prey may be [[Hoarding (animal behavior)|cached]] whole or in portions. Single items are cached at separate sites. Prey is typically stored within 10 metres of where it was procured, even if the bird is outside its own territory. In the winter the primary cache is earthworms, while during the summer the trend is toward cicadas. South Island robins have a very good memory of their storage sites; a male was observed to empty as many as five consecutive caches before returning the stores to his mate during incubation.<ref name=Powlesland>{{cite journal|last=Powlesland|first=R. G.|year=1980|title=Food-Storing Behavior of the South Island Robin|journal=Mauri Ora|volume=8|pages=11}}</ref> The birds have demonstrated an ability to differentiate and prioritise caches of varying sizes, up to 12 total items, without any training, which appears to be the highest recorded numerical competency of any wild animal.<ref name=HuntBurns>{{cite journal|last1=Hunt|first1=Simon|last2=Low|first2=Jason|last3=Burns|first3=K.C.|year=2008|title=Adaptive numerical competency in a food-hoarding songbird|journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society of London B: Biological Sciences|volume=275|issue=1649|pages=2373\u20132379|doi=10.1098/rspb.2008.0702|pmc=2603231|pmid=18611847}}</ref> Because of its high metabolic rate, a robin might spend as much as 90% of its day foraging or storing during the winter.<ref name=PowleslandB/> South Island robins have also been observed to eat berries on occasion; however, these are not cached.<ref name=Worthy/>\n\n===Vocalisation===\n[[File:Southislandrobin.jpg|thumb|right|South Island robin]]\nA male's call during non-breeding season is a series of loud notes with descending frequency which start in rapid succession and finish slowly. During breeding season, the males resort to full song to court the females. Full song is a loud, clear, and continuous song which can last for more than 30 minutes with very brief pauses, and is typically sung from the canopy or an [[Rainforest#Emergent layer|emergent]] tree.<ref name=PowleslandA/> Singing also appears to be performed as part of a strategic regulation of body mass. While robins sing during the [[Dawn chorus (birds)|dawn chorus]] as well as throughout the day, they seem to increase their singing according to food availability. When they have had more food, they will increase energetic behaviours such as singing to arrive at a strategic mass by dusk. Thus, even though two robins might begin the day with different weights, they will end the day with similar weights. A side effect of this behaviour might be the showcasing of a particular male's ability to sequester resources: the longer he sings, the more capable he is of finding food, and thus a better candidate for a mate.<ref name=Barnett>{{cite journal|last1=Barnett|first1=Craig A.|last2=Briskie|first2=James V.|year=2011|title=Strategic Regulation of Body Mass and Singing Behavior in New Zealand Robins|journal=Ethology|volume=117|issue=1|pages=28\u201336|doi=10.1111/j.1439-0310.2010.01844.x}}</ref>\n\n==Conservation==\n\nThe South Island robin is listed as being of [[least concern]] on the [[IUCN Red List]].<ref name=IUCN/> However, the Stewart Island robin (''Petroica australis rakiura'') has gone through a couple of bottlenecked populations recently because of deforestation and habitat loss, as well as introduced predators, such as rats, stoats, and feral cats.<ref name=Hale></ref> Because of this sharp decline in the Stewart Island population, several attempts have been made to translocate the Stewart Island robin to other islands nearby where introduced predators do not exist or have been eradicated (see [[South Island robin#Distribution|above]]. However, many of these translocations have involved 12 or fewer colonising individuals, making inbreeding nearly unavoidable. This has led to some apparent immunocompetency issues as well as reproduction problems. On Motuara Island high rates of hatching failure as well as fewer clutches were observed.<ref name=Hale/> Inbreeding and its genetic and immunological consequences therefore remain a concern with this subspecies.\n\nIn contrast, birds in the South Island do not show much genetic loss in comparison with historical populations, although their distribution on the island has become increasingly fragmented.<ref name=Taylor>{{cite journal|last1=Taylor|first1=S. S.|last2=Boessenkool|first2=S.|last3=Jamieson|first3=I. G.|year=2008|title=Genetic monogamy in two long\u2010lived New Zealand passerines|journal=Journal of Avian Biology|volume=39|issue=5|pages=579\u2013583|doi=10.1111/j.0908-8857.2008.04331.x}}</ref>\n\n==South Island robins and 1080 poison==\n\nA number of robin deaths have been recorded as a result of accidental [[sodium fluoroacetate|1080]] poisoning following pest control operations.<ref name=spurr>{{cite book|last=Spurr|first=E.|year=2000|chapter=Impacts of possum control on non-target species|editor=T.L. Montague|title=The brushtail possum: biology, impact and management of an introduced marsupial|publisher=Manaaki Whenua Press|location=Lincoln}}</ref> Most of these were associated with four specific operations in the 1980s that used poor-quality carrot baits.<ref name=\"pce\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pce.parliament.nz/publications/all-publications/evaluating-the-use-of-1080-predators-poisons-and-silent-forests/|title=Evaluating the use of 1080: Predators, poisons and silent forests|date=June 2011|publisher=Parliamentary Commissioner for the Environment|accessdate=7 June 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110614233345/http://www.pce.parliament.nz/publications/all-publications/evaluating-the-use-of-1080-predators-poisons-and-silent-forests|archivedate=14 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> These instances aside, robins have generally responded well to pest control programmes using aerial 1080 operations, with increased chick and adult survival, and increases in population size.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Powlesland|first1=R. G.|last2=Knegtmans|first2=J. W.|last3=Marshall|first3=I. S. J.|year=1999|title=Costs and benefits of aerial 1080 possum control operations using carrot baits to North Island robins (Petroica australis longipes), Pureora Forest Park|journal=New Zealand Journal of Ecology|volume=1999|pages=149\u2013159|url=http://www.lincoln.ac.nz/PageFiles/7074/3474_Powleslandetal__s10663.pdf}}</ref> A 2012 scientific study of a [[Bird ringing|marked]] population by the [[University of Otago]] during a contemporary 1080 poison operation using cereal baits showed no negative impact on robins and suggested a likely population increase by reducing predation pressure from introduced mammals.<ref name=\"TVNZ One News\">{{cite news |url=http://tvnz.co.nz/national-news/study-finds-1080-has-positive-effect-bird-population-video-4844337 |title=Study finds 1080 has positive effect on bird population |author=TVNZ |date=22 April 2012 |work=[[TVNZ]] |accessdate=26 April 2012}}</ref><!-- DEAD LINK Schadewinkel et al. |title=The effect of aerial application of 1080 cereal baits for possum control on South Island robin (Petroica australis) in the Silver Peaks, Dunedin'|url=http://tbfree.org.nz/Portals/0/Research/1080%20-%20robin%20report_final-revised.pdf -->\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.doc.govt.nz/conservation/native-animals/birds/land-birds/nz-robin-toutouwai/ New Zealand Robin] on [[Department of Conservation (New Zealand)|Department of Conservation]] website\n* [http://www.nzbirds.com/birds/toutouwai.html Factsheet on toutouwai, the New Zealand robin] at NZBirds.com\n* [http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/1966/robin/1/ Information about New Zealand robins] on [[Te Ara: The Encyclopedia of New Zealand|Te Ara]]\n* [http://www.doc.org.nz/upload/documents/science-and-technical/docts13.pdf Protocols for monitoring New Zealand robins(Petroica australis)] - [[Department of Conservation (New Zealand)|Department of Conservation]] Technical Series No. 13\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bwLBfaX4VjE/ Video footage of New Zealand robins] on the [[Animal Health Board (New Zealand)|Animal Health Board]] YouTube Channel\n\n{{Petroicidae}}\n{{Birds of New Zealand}}\n{{Portal bar|Birds|New Zealand}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1051396}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:robin, South Island}}\n[[Category:Petroica|South Island robin]]\n[[Category:Birds of the South Island]]\n[[Category:Endemic fauna of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1788|South Island robin]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Anders Sparrman]]\n", "name_user": "Rogermccart", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDistribution:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/South_Island_robin"}
{"title_page": "Essex and Suffolk Water", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name  = Essex and Suffolk Water\n| logo  = Essex & Suffolk Water logo.png\n| type  = [[Private company|Private]]\n|image=\t\n|image_caption = \n| foundation    = \n| location      = \n| num_employees =\n| parent        = [[Northumbrian Water Group]]\n| industry      = [[Water supply]] services\n| homepage      = {{url|www.eswater.co.uk}}\n}}\n'''Essex and Suffolk Water''' is a [[Water industry|water supply]] company in the [[United Kingdom]]. It operates in two geographically distinct areas, one serving parts of [[Norfolk]] and [[Suffolk]], and the other serving parts of [[Essex]] and [[Greater London]]. The total population served is 1.8 million. Essex and Suffolk is a 'water only' supplier, with sewerage services provided by [[Anglian Water]] and [[Thames Water]] within its areas of supply. It is part of the [[Northumbrian Water Group]].\n\n==History==\nThe South Essex Waterworks Company and the Southend Waterworks Company merged to form the Essex Water Company in 1970. In 1994 the Essex Water Company merged with Suffolk Water Company to form Essex and Suffolk Water. Since 2000 it has been part of [[Northumbrian Water Group|Northumbrian Water]], but continues to trade under the Essex and Suffolk Water name in the area.{{sfn |ESW |2006 |p=21}}\n\n{{Ahnentafel\n|title=Company history of Essex and Suffolk Water\n|collapsed=yes\n|width=100%\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|boxstyle_5=background-color: #9fe;\n|boxstyle_6=background-color: #7fe;\n|1= Essex & Suffolk Water (from 1994)\n|2= Essex Water (1970-1994)\n|3= Suffolk Water plc (1991-1994) \n|4= Southend Waterworks Company (1865-1970)\n|5= South Essex Waterworks Company (1861-1970)\n|7= East Anglian Water Company (1962-1991)\n|14= Great Yarmouth Waterworks Company (1853-1962)\n|15= Lowestoft Waterworks Company (1948-1962)\n|31= Lowestoft Water and Gas Company (1897-1948)\n|63= Lowestoft Gas, Water and Markets Company (1853-1897)\n}}\n\n===Southend Waterworks Company===\nThe Southend Waterworks Company had its origins in [[Southend-on-Sea]] in 1865 when a private undertaking constructed a well in Milton Road. A pumping station pumped the water to a reservoir on Cambridge Road. In 1871, the Southend Waterworks Company Limited was formed, and bought the works. The company became a [[statutory undertaker]] in 1879,<ref>Southend Waterworks Act 1879 (42 & 43 Vict. c.cxx)</ref>{{sfn |SWC |1948}} which restricted the amount of money they could borrow, the profits they could retain and the dividend payable to shareholders,{{sfn |Ofwat |2006 |p=6}} but gave them powers to lay pipes beneath public streets and on private land.\n\nBy 1924, the company were supplying an area of {{convert|160|sqmi|km2}} bounded on the south by the [[River Thames]], on the north by the [[River Crouch]], and stretching westwards to the outskirts of [[Shenfield]]. As the volume of water required increased, additional wells were sunk, until there were 36 wells or boreholes in operation. They penetrated a layer of London clay near the surface, and continued into the sands of the Lower London tertiary deposits below that, but the yields obtained were generally poor and gradually diminished over time. In 1921 the company started to look at extracting water from rivers, but failed to obtain parliamentary approval for a joint scheme with the South Essex Waterworks Company to obtain water from the [[River Stour, Suffolk|River Stour]] on the border between Essex and Suffolk. They therefore developed a scheme to extract water from the [[River Blackwater, Essex|River Blackwater]], the [[River Chelmer]] and its tributary, the [[River Ter]]. An [[Act of Parliament]] was obtained in August 1924,<ref>Southend Waterworks Act 1924 (14 & 15 Geo. 5 c.lxii)</ref> to enable construction of Langford Works, to the west of [[Maldon, Essex|Maldon]].{{sfn |SWC |1948}}\n\nThe project involved the construction of intakes on the Chelmer and Ter, so that water from either or both could be fed into a concrete pipeline which was {{convert|33|in|cm}} in diameter and {{convert|2.5|mi|km}} long. The water flowed by gravity along the pipeline to two sedimentation reservoirs each covering {{convert|10.1|acre|ha}} and capable of holding {{convert|30|e6impgal|Ml}}. Water from the Blackwater intake at Langford Mill is pumped to the sedimentation reservoirs. From there the water flows by gravity to the Langford pumping station. In order to maintain the quality of the water, effluent discharged from the [[Chelmsford]] sewage treatment works on the Chelmer and the [[Witham]] sewage treatment works on the Blackwater was piped to new outfalls below the intakes.{{sfn |SWC |1948}}\n\nWhen built, the Langford pumping station contained two triple-expansion steam engines, with room for a third, which was fitted in 1931.{{sfn|Chaplin|Allen|2011}} There were used in pairs, and each drove a low lift pump to transfer water to the treatment works, and a high lift pump to take treated water and pump it along a {{convert|28|in|cm|adj=on}} [[cast iron]] pipe to Southend. The pipe crossed below the River Crouch at [[Hullbridge]], where shafts were built on either side of the river, and a tunnel was constructed between them. The water main is formed of twin steel tubes within the tunnel. The engines were normally worked in pairs, and a pair could deliver {{convert|8|e6impgal|Ml}} per day. In August 1927, water from the Chelmer started to be used, and between then and 1945, 96 per cent of the water supplied by Southend Waterworks came from Langford. The wells and boreholes were maintained, to provide a backup supply when necessary.{{sfn |SWC |1948}}\n\nIn 1960, work began on replacing the steam engines at Langford pumping station with semi-automatic electric pumps. The project cost \u00a3260,000, and was formally inaugurated on 31 October 1963, when Sir George Chaplin, the Chairman of [[Essex County Council]] switched on the new pumps. In the late 1960s, construction of a new treatment works next to the storage reservoirs began. The works cost \u00a31.5 million, and were opened on 30 June 1970. They can produce {{convert|12|e6impgal|Ml}} of treated water per day. Earlier that year, the Essex Water Order<ref>Essex Water Order 1970 S.I. 1970/786: Regrouping Order: transfer of the water undertakings of certain local authorities and the Southend Waterworks Company to the South Essex Waterworks Company</ref> was passed by Parliament, and on 1 April Southend Waterworks Company amalgamated with South Essex Waterworks Company to become the Essex Water Company. Negotiations between Maldon District Council, Essex and Suffolk Water and other interested parties in 1996 resulted in the Langford pumping station and its one remaining engine, dating from 1931, becoming the fledgling [[Museum of Power]].{{sfn|Chaplin|Allen|2011}}\n\n===South Essex Waterworks Company===\nThe South Essex Waterworks Company was formed in 1861, and supplied drinking water to an area of {{convert|103|sqmi|km2}} stretching from [[Grays, Essex|Grays]] to [[East Ham]] and from [[Brentwood, Essex|Brentwood]] to the [[River Thames]]. Water was obtained from boreholes sunk into the chalk [[aquifer]] underlying the area, but by the time of the [[First World War]], these supplies were not sufficient to meet the demand for water, and so the company looked further afield. Following the failure of the joint scheme with Southend Waterworks Company, they obtained an Act of Parliament in 1928<ref>South Essex Waterworks Act 1928 (18 & 19 Geo. 5 c. lxxix)</ref> for a revised scheme which included a water treatment works at [[Langham, Essex|Langham]] with an intake from the River Stour. Treated water was pumped from the works to [[Tiptree]] works, and was pumped from there to a reservoir at [[Danbury, Essex|Danbury]]. It then flowed by gravity to another storage reservoir at [[Herongate]] and then into the distribution network. One condition of the Act was that the company had to supply water to other local authorities which were outside their original supply area.{{sfn |ESW|2006|pp=6-7}} \n\n[[File:Pumping Station - geograph.org.uk - 37807.jpg|thumb|The 1930s style pump house at Abberton Reservoir]]\nAlthough the Langham works could supply {{convert|12|e6impgal|Ml}} per day, and came online in 1932, they estimated that they would still be facing a shortage by the end of the decade. The company obtained another Act of Parliament in 1935<ref>South Essex Waterworks Act 1935 (25 & 26 Geo. 5 c. xlviii)</ref> for a second abstraction point on the Stour. This was located at [[Stratford St. Mary]], about {{convert|1.5|mi|km}} downstream from the Langham intake. A pumping station pumped up to {{convert|35|e6impgal|Ml}} of water per day to the new [[Abberton Reservoir]], and a new treatment works was built at [[Layer de la Haye]] near its northern shore. Treated water was pumped to Tiptree, where it was blended with water from Langham.{{sfn |ESW|2006|pp=6-7}} The pipeline from Stratford St. Mary was {{convert|11|mi|km}} long, while Abberton Reservoir covers an area of {{convert|1210|acre|km2}} and lies in the valley of the Layer Brook. When full, it could hold {{convert|5700|e6impgal|Ml}}. Layer treatment works could process {{convert|125|Ml|e6impgal|order=flip}} per day, and the system was designed to store water from winter rainfall for use in the summer months.{{sfn |ESW|2006|pp=4-5}}\n\nConstruction of the reservoir began in March 1936 and continued until the start of the [[Second World War]] in 1939. To pass under the [[River Colne, Essex|River Colne]], shafts were constructed on either side of the river, and a {{convert|12|ft|m|adj=on}} diameter tunnel was excavated between the shafts. The miners worked in compressed air, and twin pipes of {{convert|32|in|cm|adj=on}} diameter were run through the tunnel. The original pipeline consisted of bitumen-lined steel tubes, some {{convert|34|in|cm}} and some {{convert|36|in|cm}} in diameter. A second pipeline of {{convert|40|and|42|in|cm|adj=on|sigfig=3}} diameter pipes was subsequently installed.{{sfn |ESW|2006|pp=10-11}} Filling of the reservoir began in 1939 and was completed by the end of 1940.{{sfn |ESW|2006|p=18}} Some minor commissioning work, including the Abberton pumping station, was delayed until the end of hostilities. The project cost \u00a3500,000. Many of the construction workers came from [[County Durham|Durham]], and some stayed on to run the works, including Stanley Aldridge, who had been the Engineer, and became the General Manager of the Layer works.{{sfn |ESW|2006|p=19}}\n\n===Joint projects===\n[[File:Sluice on Kirtling Brook, Great Bradley - geograph.org.uk - 47866.jpg|left|thumb|The sluice on Kirtling Brook, where water from the Great Ouse is discharged from the Ely Ouse to Essex Transfer Scheme into the River Stour system]]\nAlthough the Southend Waterworks Company and the South Essex Waterworks Company did not formally unite until 1970, they co-operated on two major projects prior to that date. These were the construction of Hanningfield Reservoir and the Ely-Ouse to Essex Transfer Scheme.\n\nThe construction of [[Hanningfield Reservoir]], which was authorised by the Hanningfield Water Order 1950,{{sfn|ESW|2006|p=22}} and began in 1951, was a joint venture between the two companies. It was built in the Sandon Valley, to the north of [[Wickford]], and covered the hamlet of Peasdown. A {{convert|1.25|mi|km|adj=on}} mass earth dam with a [[Puddling (engineering)|puddle clay]] core was built across the north-east edge of the site, and a new {{convert|9|mi|km|adj=on}} pipeline was built from the Langford pumping station to supply the reservoir. The main contractors for the project were W&C French, and it took around 5 years to complete, with the treatment works beginning production in August 1956. The formal opening took place over a year later, when  [[Henry Brooke, Baron Brooke of Cumnor|Henry Brooke]], [[Member of parliament|MP]], the [[Minister of Housing and Local Government]], performed the ceremony in September 1957. The total cost of the project was \u00a36 million, and when full, the reservoir can hold {{convert|26075|Ml|e6impgal|order=flip}}. If supplies around {{convert|150|Ml|e6impgal|order=flip}} or treated water per day, although the maximum throughput of the works is {{convert|225|Ml|e6impgal|order=flip}} per day. Water levels fluctuate seasonally, and during the winter months, up to {{convert|240|Ml|e6impgal|order=flip}} per day are pumped into the reservoir via the Langford pipeline.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.eswater.co.uk/media-centre/3190_3147.aspx |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180111110227/https://www.eswater.co.uk/media-centre/3190_3147.aspx |archivedate=11 January 2018 |url-status=live |title=Pure Gold |publisher=Essex and Suffolk Water |date=9 August 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn order to meet the rising demands for water faced by both companies, the next major project was the Ely-Ouse to Essex Transfer Scheme. Surplus water in the [[River Great Ouse]], which would otherwise flow into the sea, was to be diverted via a series of channels, tunnels and pipelines to augment supplies to the Abberton and Hanningfield reservoirs. At the northern end, the Cut Off Channel carries the headwaters of the [[River Lark]], the [[River Little Ouse]] and the [[River Wissey]] to the Great Ouse at Denver Sluice, when those rivers are in flood. An intake was constructed at Blackdyke, close to the Little Ouse, and a tunnel carries the water to a pumping station at [[Kennett, Cambridgeshire|Kennett]]. From there a {{convert|1.83|m|ft|order=flip|adj=on}} pipeline carries the water to [[Kirtling|Kirtling Green]] Outfall, where it enters Kirtling Brook, a tributary of the River Stour. Further down the Stour, some of the water is removed from the river by [[Wixoe]] pumping station. A {{convert|1.68|m|ft|order=flip|adj=on}} diameter pipeline carries it to the [[Great Sampford]] outfall, where it is discharged into the River Pant, the name of the upper reaches of the River Blackwater.{{sfn |ESW |2006 |p=22}} Construction of the scheme was completed in 1971.{{sfn |Barty-King |1992 |p=189}}\n\n===Suffolk Water plc===\nThe Great Yarmouth Waterworks Company was set up in 1853, authorised by the Great Yarmouth Waterworks Act of that year. They built a waterworks at [[Trinity Broads|Ormesby Broad]], from where water flowed by gravity into Great Yarmouth. Two steam engines raised the water up to some filter beds.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://greatyarmouthhistory.com/perlustration/The%20Guided%20Tour.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150227123504/http://greatyarmouthhistory.com/perlustration/The%20Guided%20Tour.htm |archivedate=27 February 2015 |title=The Guided Tour |publisher=Great Yarmouth History |accessdate=27 February 2015}}</ref> The construction of the distribution network of pipes through the town was completed in 1855, when the Ormesby Waterworks was opened.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gtyarmouth.co.uk/bygones/crisp/html/crisp2.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312034450/http://www.gtyarmouth.co.uk/bygones/crisp/html/crisp2.htm |archivedate=12 March 2017 |url-status=live |title=Chronological Retrospect 1800 - 1877 |first=William |last=Finch-Crisp |publisher=Great Yarmouth History |accessdate=27 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nPublic water supply in Lowestoft also began in 1853,<ref>The Lowestoft Water, Gas and Market Act 1853 (c. xviii)</ref> with the creation of the Lowestoft Water, Gas and Market Company. They retained this name until 1897, when they became the Lowestoft Water and Gas Company.<ref>The Lowestoft Water and Gas Act 1897 (c. cx)</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/rd/a7d42d15-6c1a-4ed3-9688-4fba6d45aaeb |title=Lowestoft Water and Gas Company |publisher=The National Archives |accessdate=27 February 2015}}</ref> The company had an authorised capital of \u00a325,000, and bought the gas works for \u00a35,000. Water was supplied to a tower at Kirkley from a well at Middle West Field,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lucasbrothers.co.uk/?year=1850 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140622220227/http://www.lucasbrothers.co.uk/?year=1850 |archivedate=22 June 2014 |url-status=live |title=Messrs Lucas Brothers |accessdate=27 February 2015}}</ref> and subsequently from a lake at Bunkers Hill, [[Lound, Suffolk|Lound]]. From there it was pumped through a {{convert|5|mi|km|adj=on}} pipeline to a covered reservoir located to the north of the town.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://forebears.co.uk/england/suffolk/lowestoft |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180111052654/http://forebears.co.uk/england/suffolk/lowestoft |archivedate=11 January 2018 |url-status=live |title=Historical Description |publisher=Forebears |accessdate=27 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nBoth the company and the Great Yarmouth company were finding that the supplies were inadequate for the populations of the two towns, particularly are there was a large seasonal tourist trade, and in 1906, they attempted to get authorisation for extracting water from the [[River Bure]]. The bill faced a rough passage through Parliament, as there were objections to parts of it from [[Norfolk County Council]], the Great Yarmouth Corporation, the Great Yarmouth Court Commissioners, the London Drainage Commissioners, the [[Ecclesiastical Commissioners]] for England, and some private individuals. The chief concerns were that removing water from the Bure would impede navigation, and that the quality of the water would be poor, and unfit to supply as drinking water.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/lords/1906/mar/13/great-yarmouth-waterworks-and-lowestoft |title=Great Yarmouth Waterworks and Lowestoft Water and Gas Bill |publisher=Hansard |accessdate=27 February 2015}}</ref> However, the bill eventually became the Great Yarmouth Waterworks and Lowestoft Water and Gas Act 1907.<ref>The Great Yarmouth Water-works and Lowestoft Water and Gas Act 1907 (c. lxxxiv)</ref><ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/28044/page/5117/data.pdf |title=Westminster, July 26, 1907 |work=The London Gazette |date=26 July 1907 |issue=28044}}</ref>\n\nThe two companies amalgamated in 1962 to become the East Anglian Water Company. The merger was sanctioned by the East Anglian Water Order 1962,<ref>The East Anglian Water Order 1961 S.I. 1961/2291</ref> using the powers of the [[Water Act 1945]]. By this time the Lowestoft Water and Gas Company was known as the Lowestoft Water Company, as all gas companies had been [[Gas Act 1948|nationalised in 1948]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.acraew.org.uk/sites/default/files/uploads/Norfolk/THE%20STAITHE%20-%20ORMESBY%20ST%20MICHAEL%20-%20GREAT%20YARMOUTH%20DISTRICT%20NO.CL.128.pdf |title=Hearing of the Commons Registration Act 1965 |publisher=Association of Commons Registration Authorities |accessdate=27 February 2015}}</ref> A further change of name occurred on 18 January 1991, when it became Suffolk Water plc, and the new company was taken over by Essex Water on 8 April 1994, to become Essex and Suffolk Water. Both were owned by the French company {{ill|Lyonnaise des Eaux-Dumez|fr|Lyonnaise des eaux}} at the time.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.suffolkarchives.co.uk/collections/getrecord/GB175_1176_2_2_19_602 |title=Search results in the Suffolk Record Office collections |publisher=Suffolk County Council |accessdate=27 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Essex and Suffolk Water===\nIn order to provide improved supplies to Great Yarmouth, the company bought most of the [[Trinity Broads]] in 1995. These are isolated from the [[River Bure]] by a narrow channel, and have been further protected by the installation of a sluice gate. They were designated as a [[Site of Special Scientific Interest]] in 1998.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eswater.co.uk/TrinityBroads.aspx |publisher=Essex and Suffolk Water |title=Trinity Broads |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101003104230/http://www.eswater.co.uk/TrinityBroads.aspx |archivedate=3 October 2010 |accessdate=6 March 2015}}</ref> Osmesby Works is situated by the side of Ormesby Broad, and can treat water from the broads. A second source of water is pumped some {{convert|18|mi|km}} from the River Bure to the works. Parts of the works date from the 1930s, and others from the 1950s, but a major upgrade was completed in 2005, to enhance the treatment of water from the broads, which is affected by [[algal bloom]] for around a quarter of each year.{{sfn |Walker |2004 |p=233}}  \n\nIn order to meet long term supply requirements, the company looked at several options, and in 1997 settled on expanding the capacity of Abberton Reservoir. After ten years of design work and a lengthy tendering process, work began in January 2010 on a project costed at \u00a3150 million, to increase the capacity of the reservoir by 58 per cent, and to upgrade the capacity of the Ely-Ouse Essex Transfer Scheme.{{sfn |Wilson |2012 |p=240}} The clay core of the main dam was raised by {{convert|9.5|ft|m}}, to allow the water level to be raised by {{convert|10.5|ft|m}}, increasing the surface area of the reservoir from {{convert|1.8|sqmi|km2}} to {{convert|2.5|sqmi|km2}}.{{sfn |Wilson |2012 |p=241}} The original pumping station which pumped water to Layer de la Haye treatment works would have been submerged by the new water levels, and so had to be demolished and rebuilt at a higher level. In order to keep the system operational while this was being done, a temporary pumping station was built on the shore of the reservoir.{{sfn |Wilson |2012 |p=242}} The new station can deliver {{convert|231|Ml|e6impgal|order=flip}} of raw water per day to the works.{{sfn |Wilson |2012 |p=241}} Other enhancements at the reservoir site included the construction of a new visitor centre for the [[Essex Wildlife Trust]], and work on the B1026 causeway, which crossed the reservoir at a height where it would be below the level of the new water surface.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.eswater.co.uk/your-home/your-services/abberton-enhancement.aspx |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160314164248/https://www.eswater.co.uk/your-home/your-services/abberton-enhancement.aspx |archivedate=14 March 2016 |title=Reservoir enhancement |publisher=Essex and Suffolk Water |accessdate=6 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nWith the capacity of the reservoir increased from {{convert|26000|to|41000|Ml|e6impgal|order=flip}}, two new pipelines were constructed, to improve the transfer of water from the Ouse.{{sfn |Jenkins |2013 |p=253}} The Ely Ouse to Essex Transfer Scheme was licensed to allow {{convert|455|Ml|e6impgal|order=flip}} per day to be transferred, but the pumps at the Kennett pumping station could not deliver this volume, and the maximum permitted discharge into the river at Kirtling Green was {{convert|344|Ml|e6impgal|order=flip}} per day. As part of the upgrade, three additional pumps were installed at Kennett.{{sfn |Jenkins |2013 |p=255}} Around {{convert|9.6|mi|km}} of new underground pipeline was constructed from Kirtling Green in Suffolk, along the banks of the Stour to Wixoe, where the water discharges into the river. Most is {{convert|4|ft|m|adj=on}} in diameter, but this reduces to {{convert|3.3|ft|m}} for the final {{convert|2.1|mi|km}}, where the gradient is steeper.{{sfn |Jenkins |2013 |p=253}} It can deliver an additional {{convert|145|Ml|e6impgal|order=flip}} per day into the river system.{{sfn |Jenkins |2013 |p=255}} Further down the river, a new pumping station was constructed at Wormingford, to remove the water from the river and pump it to Abberton. The pumping station pumps the water for approximately {{convert|1.2|mi|km|0}} to a break tank, from where it can flow by gravity to the reservoir. Most of the two pipelines were installed using [[cut and cover]] techniques, but the southern pipeline passes under the [[River Colne, Essex|River Colne]] and beneath the [[A12 road (England)|A12 road]] and the [[Great Eastern Main Line|East Coast railway]] to the west of [[Colchester]]. Twin shafts, {{convert|23|ft|m|0}} in diameter and {{convert|66|ft|m}} deep were excavated, and {{convert|490|ft|m}} of {{convert|5|ft|m|adj=on}} diameter bored tunnel passed under both the road and the railway. The pipeline was then laid through the tunnel and grouted in.{{sfn |Jenkins |2013 |pp=253-254}} The entire project was completed in 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.eswater.co.uk/_assets/documents/Timescales.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402125947/https://www.eswater.co.uk/_assets/documents/Timescales.pdf |archivedate=2 April 2015 |url-status=live|title=Timescales |publisher=Essex and Suffolk Water |accessdate=6 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Supply area==\nThe company supplies water to an area of {{convert|2861|sqkm|sqmi|order=flip}} in southeast Norfolk, east Suffolk, Essex and the London boroughs of [[London Borough of Barking and Dagenham|Barking and Dagenham]], [[London Borough of Havering|Havering]] and [[London Borough of Redbridge|Redbridge]] in Greater London. The total population served is 1.8 million, through over 735,000 domestic connections and over 47,000 non-household connections.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.eswater.co.uk/media-centre/3190_2567.aspx |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150222151924/https://www.eswater.co.uk/media-centre/3190_2567.aspx |archivedate=22 February 2015 |url-status=live |title=Winning the right to bid for \u00a31.5 billion worth of work |publisher=Essex and Suffolk Water |accessdate=22 February 2015}}</ref> Essex and Suffolk is a 'water only' supplier, with sewerage services supplied by [[Anglian Water]] (Essex, Norfolk, Suffolk and part of Upminster) and [[Thames Water]] (Greater London and part of Brentwood).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eswater.co.uk/business/btariffs-and-charges.aspx |title=Unmetered charges |publisher=Essex and Suffolk Water |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130103213649/http://www.eswater.co.uk/business/btariffs-and-charges.aspx |archivedate=3 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{Refbegin}}\n*{{cite book\n  |first=Hugh |last=Barty-King\n  |title=Water The Book\n  |publisher=Quiller Press\n  |year=1992\n  |isbn=978-1-870948-74-6\n  |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite web\n  |url=http://www.museumofpower.org.uk/History.html\n  |first1=Patrick |last1=Chaplin\n  |first2=Irene |last2=Allen\n  |title=Station History\n  |publisher=Museum of Power, Langford\n  |year=2011\n  |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite web\n  |url=http://www.eswater.co.uk/_assets/documents/Abberton_History_Brochure.pdf\n  |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305145713/https://www.eswater.co.uk/_assets/documents/Abberton_History_Brochure.pdf\n  |archivedate=5 March 2015 |url-status=live\n  |last=ESW\n  |title=Abberton Reservoir Expansion Project\n  |publisher=Essex and Suffolk Water \n  |year=2006\n  |accessdate=20 February 2015\n  |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite web\n  |url=http://www.waterprojectsonline.com/case_studies/2013/E&S_Abberton_Pipeline_2013.pdf\n  |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304061419/http://www.waterprojectsonline.com/case_studies/2013/E%26S_Abberton_Pipeline_2013.pdf\n  |archivedate=4 March 2016\n  |url-status=live\n  |first=Jim\n  |last=Jenkins\n  |title=Abberton Pipelines Project\n  |publisher=Water Projects Online\n  |year=2013\n  |ref=harv\n  |access-date=11 August 2019\n  }}\n*{{cite web\n  |url=http://www.ofwat.gov.uk/publications/commissioned/rpt_com_devwatindust270106.pdf\n  |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150716224258/http://www.ofwat.gov.uk/publications/commissioned/rpt_com_devwatindust270106.pdf\n  |archivedate=16 July 2015\n  |last=Ofwat\n  |title=The Development of the Water Industry in England and Wales\n  |year=2006\n  |publisher=[[OFWAT]]\n  |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book\n  |url=http://www.itsaboutmaldon.co.uk/langford_pumping_station/\n  |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171024124510/http://www.itsaboutmaldon.co.uk/langford_pumping_station/\n  |archivedate=24 October 2017\n  |url-status=live\n  |last=SWC\n  |title=An illustrated description of the works at Langford, Maldon\n  |publisher=Southend Waterworks Company\n  |year=1948\n  |ref=harv\n  |access-date=21 February 2015\n  }}\n*{{cite web\n  |url=http://www.waterprojectsonline.com/case_studies/2004/E&S_Ormesby_2004.pdf\n  |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304103442/http://www.waterprojectsonline.com/case_studies/2004/E%26S_Ormesby_2004.pdf\n  |archivedate=4 March 2016\n  |url-status=live\n  |first=Guy\n  |last=Walker\n  |title=Ormesby WTW - Trihalomethane Project\n  |publisher=Water Projects Online\n  |year=2004\n  |ref=harv\n  |access-date=11 August 2019\n  }}\n*{{cite web\n  |url=http://www.waterprojectsonline.com/case_studies/2012/E&S_Abberton_2012.pdf\n  |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303232516/http://www.waterprojectsonline.com/case_studies/2012/E%26S_Abberton_2012.pdf\n  |archivedate=3 March 2016\n  |url-status=live\n  |first=Daniel\n  |last=Wilson\n  |title=Abberton Reservoir enhancement\n  |publisher=Water Projects Online\n  |year=2012\n  |ref=harv\n  |access-date=11 August 2019\n  }}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website}}\n\n{{Water companies of the United Kingdom}}\n{{Water supply and sanitation in London}}\n\n[[Category:Water companies of England]]\n[[Category:Companies supplying water and sanitation to London]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name  = Essex and Suffolk Water\n| logo  = Essex & Suffolk Water logo.png\n| type  = [[Private company|Private]]\n|image=\t\n|image_caption = \n| foundation    = \n| location      = \n| num_employees =\n| parent        = [[Northumbrian Water Group]]\n| industry      = [[Water supply]] services\n| homepage      = {{url|www.eswater.co.uk}}\n}}\n'''Essex and Suffolk Water''' is a [[Water industry|water supply]] company in the [[United Kingdom]]. It operates in two geographically distinct areas, one serving parts of [[Norfolk]] and [[Suffolk]], and the other serving parts of [[Essex]] and [[Greater London]]. The total population served is 1.8 million. Essex and Suffolk is a 'water only' supplier, with sewerage services provided by [[Anglian Water]] and [[Thames Water]] within its areas of supply. It is part of the [[Northumbrian Water Group]].\n\n==History==\nThe South Essex Waterworks Company and the Southend Waterworks Company merged to form the Essex Water Company in 1970. In 1994 the Essex Water Company merged with Suffolk Water Company to form Essex and Suffolk Water. Since 2000 it has been part of [[Northumbrian Water Group|Northumbrian Water]], but continues to trade under the Essex and Suffolk Water name in the area.{{sfn |ESW |2006 |p=21}}\n\n{{Ahnentafel\n|title=Company history of Essex and Suffolk Water\n|collapsed=yes\n|width=100%\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|boxstyle_5=background-color: #9fe;\n|boxstyle_6=background-color: #7fe;\n|1= Essex & Suffolk Water (from 1994)\n|2= Essex Water (1970-1994)\n|3= Suffolk Water plc (1991-1994) \n|4= Southend Waterworks Company (1865-1970)\n|5= South Essex Waterworks Company (1861-1970)\n|7= East Anglian Water Company (1962-1991)\n|14= Great Yarmouth Waterworks Company (1853-1962)\n|15= Lowestoft Waterworks Company (1948-1962)\n|31= Lowestoft Water and Gas Company (1897-1948)\n|63= Lowestoft Gas, Water and Markets Company (1853-1897)\n}}\n\n===Southend Waterworks Company===\nThe Southend Waterworks Company had its origins in [[Southend-on-Sea]] in 1865 when a private undertaking constructed a well in Milton Road. A pumping station pumped the water to a reservoir on Cambridge Road. In 1871, the Southend Waterworks Company Limited was formed, and bought the works. The company became a [[statutory undertaker]] in 1879,<ref>Southend Waterworks Act 1879 (42 & 43 Vict. c.cxx)</ref>{{sfn |SWC |1948}} which restricted the amount of money they could borrow, the profits they could retain and the dividend payable to shareholders,{{sfn |Ofwat |2006 |p=6}} but gave them powers to lay pipes beneath public streets and on private land.\n\nBy 1924, the company were supplying an area of {{convert|160|sqmi|km2}} bounded on the south by the [[River Thames]], on the north by the [[River Crouch]], and stretching westwards to the outskirts of [[Shenfield]]. As the volume of water required increased, additional wells were sunk, until there were 36 wells or boreholes in operation. They penetrated a layer of London clay near the surface, and continued into the sands of the Lower London tertiary deposits below that, but the yields obtained were generally poor and gradually diminished over time. In 1921 the company started to look at extracting water from rivers, but failed to obtain parliamentary approval for a joint scheme with the South Essex Waterworks Company to obtain water from the [[River Stour, Suffolk|River Stour]] on the border between Essex and Suffolk. They therefore developed a scheme to extract water from the [[River Blackwater, Essex|River Blackwater]], the [[River Chelmer]] and its tributary, the [[River Ter]]. An [[Act of Parliament]] was obtained in August 1924,<ref>Southend Waterworks Act 1924 (14 & 15 Geo. 5 c.lxii)</ref> to enable construction of Langford Works, to the west of [[Maldon, Essex|Maldon]].{{sfn |SWC |1948}}\n\nThe project involved the construction of intakes on the Chelmer and Ter, so that water from either or both could be fed into a concrete pipeline which was {{convert|33|in|cm}} in diameter and {{convert|2.5|mi|km}} long. The water flowed by gravity along the pipeline to two sedimentation reservoirs each covering {{convert|10.1|acre|ha}} and capable of holding {{convert|30|e6impgal|Ml}}. Water from the Blackwater intake at Langford Mill is pumped to the sedimentation reservoirs. From there the water flows by gravity to the Langford pumping station. In order to maintain the quality of the water, effluent discharged from the [[Chelmsford]] sewage treatment works on the Chelmer and the [[Witham]] sewage treatment works on the Blackwater was piped to new outfalls below the intakes.{{sfn |SWC |1948}}\n\nWhen built, the Langford pumping station contained two triple-expansion steam engines, with room for a third, which was fitted in 1931.{{sfn|Chaplin|Allen|2011}} There were used in pairs, and each drove a low lift pump to transfer water to the treatment works, and a high lift pump to take treated water and pump it along a {{convert|28|in|cm|adj=on}} [[cast iron]] pipe to Southend. The pipe crossed below the River Crouch at [[Hullbridge]], where shafts were built on either side of the river, and a tunnel was constructed between them. The water main is formed of twin steel tubes within the tunnel. The engines were normally worked in pairs, and a pair could deliver {{convert|8|e6impgal|Ml}} per day. In August 1927, water from the Chelmer started to be used, and between then and 1945, 96 per cent of the water supplied by Southend Waterworks came from Langford. The wells and boreholes were maintained, to provide a backup supply when necessary.{{sfn |SWC |1948}}\n\nIn 1960, work began on replacing the steam engines at Langford pumping station with semi-automatic electric pumps. The project cost \u00a3260,000, and was formally inaugurated on 31 October 1963, when Sir George Chaplin, the Chairman of [[Essex County Council]] switched on the new pumps. In the late 1960s, construction of a new treatment works next to the storage reservoirs began. The works cost \u00a31.5 million, and were opened on 30 June 1970. They can produce {{convert|12|e6impgal|Ml}} of treated water per day. Earlier that year, the Essex Water Order<ref>Essex Water Order 1970 S.I. 1970/786: Regrouping Order: transfer of the water undertakings of certain local authorities and the Southend Waterworks Company to the South Essex Waterworks Company</ref> was passed by Parliament, and on 1 April Southend Waterworks Company amalgamated with South Essex Waterworks Company to become the Essex Water Company. Negotiations between Maldon District Council, Essex and Suffolk Water and other interested parties in 1996 resulted in the Langford pumping station and its one remaining engine, dating from 1931, becoming the fledgling [[Museum of Power]].{{sfn|Chaplin|Allen|2011}}\n\n===South Essex Waterworks Company===\nThe South Essex Waterworks Company was formed in 1861, and supplied drinking water to an area of {{convert|103|sqmi|km2}} stretching from [[Grays]] to [[East Ham]] and from [[Brentwood, Essex|Brentwood]] to the [[River Thames]]. Water was obtained from boreholes sunk into the chalk [[aquifer]] underlying the area, but by the time of the [[First World War]], these supplies were not sufficient to meet the demand for water, and so the company looked further afield. Following the failure of the joint scheme with Southend Waterworks Company, they obtained an Act of Parliament in 1928<ref>South Essex Waterworks Act 1928 (18 & 19 Geo. 5 c. lxxix)</ref> for a revised scheme which included a water treatment works at [[Langham, Essex|Langham]] with an intake from the River Stour. Treated water was pumped from the works to [[Tiptree]] works, and was pumped from there to a reservoir at [[Danbury, Essex|Danbury]]. It then flowed by gravity to another storage reservoir at [[Herongate]] and then into the distribution network. One condition of the Act was that the company had to supply water to other local authorities which were outside their original supply area.{{sfn |ESW|2006|pp=6-7}} \n\n[[File:Pumping Station - geograph.org.uk - 37807.jpg|thumb|The 1930s style pump house at Abberton Reservoir]]\nAlthough the Langham works could supply {{convert|12|e6impgal|Ml}} per day, and came online in 1932, they estimated that they would still be facing a shortage by the end of the decade. The company obtained another Act of Parliament in 1935<ref>South Essex Waterworks Act 1935 (25 & 26 Geo. 5 c. xlviii)</ref> for a second abstraction point on the Stour. This was located at [[Stratford St. Mary]], about {{convert|1.5|mi|km}} downstream from the Langham intake. A pumping station pumped up to {{convert|35|e6impgal|Ml}} of water per day to the new [[Abberton Reservoir]], and a new treatment works was built at [[Layer de la Haye]] near its northern shore. Treated water was pumped to Tiptree, where it was blended with water from Langham.{{sfn |ESW|2006|pp=6-7}} The pipeline from Stratford St. Mary was {{convert|11|mi|km}} long, while Abberton Reservoir covers an area of {{convert|1210|acre|km2}} and lies in the valley of the Layer Brook. When full, it could hold {{convert|5700|e6impgal|Ml}}. Layer treatment works could process {{convert|125|Ml|e6impgal|order=flip}} per day, and the system was designed to store water from winter rainfall for use in the summer months.{{sfn |ESW|2006|pp=4-5}}\n\nConstruction of the reservoir began in March 1936 and continued until the start of the [[Second World War]] in 1939. To pass under the [[River Colne, Essex|River Colne]], shafts were constructed on either side of the river, and a {{convert|12|ft|m|adj=on}} diameter tunnel was excavated between the shafts. The miners worked in compressed air, and twin pipes of {{convert|32|in|cm|adj=on}} diameter were run through the tunnel. The original pipeline consisted of bitumen-lined steel tubes, some {{convert|34|in|cm}} and some {{convert|36|in|cm}} in diameter. A second pipeline of {{convert|40|and|42|in|cm|adj=on|sigfig=3}} diameter pipes was subsequently installed.{{sfn |ESW|2006|pp=10-11}} Filling of the reservoir began in 1939 and was completed by the end of 1940.{{sfn |ESW|2006|p=18}} Some minor commissioning work, including the Abberton pumping station, was delayed until the end of hostilities. The project cost \u00a3500,000. Many of the construction workers came from [[County Durham|Durham]], and some stayed on to run the works, including Stanley Aldridge, who had been the Engineer, and became the General Manager of the Layer works.{{sfn |ESW|2006|p=19}}\n\n===Joint projects===\n[[File:Sluice on Kirtling Brook, Great Bradley - geograph.org.uk - 47866.jpg|left|thumb|The sluice on Kirtling Brook, where water from the Great Ouse is discharged from the Ely Ouse to Essex Transfer Scheme into the River Stour system]]\nAlthough the Southend Waterworks Company and the South Essex Waterworks Company did not formally unite until 1970, they co-operated on two major projects prior to that date. These were the construction of Hanningfield Reservoir and the Ely-Ouse to Essex Transfer Scheme.\n\nThe construction of [[Hanningfield Reservoir]], which was authorised by the Hanningfield Water Order 1950,{{sfn|ESW|2006|p=22}} and began in 1951, was a joint venture between the two companies. It was built in the Sandon Valley, to the north of [[Wickford]], and covered the hamlet of Peasdown. A {{convert|1.25|mi|km|adj=on}} mass earth dam with a [[Puddling (engineering)|puddle clay]] core was built across the north-east edge of the site, and a new {{convert|9|mi|km|adj=on}} pipeline was built from the Langford pumping station to supply the reservoir. The main contractors for the project were W&C French, and it took around 5 years to complete, with the treatment works beginning production in August 1956. The formal opening took place over a year later, when  [[Henry Brooke, Baron Brooke of Cumnor|Henry Brooke]], [[Member of parliament|MP]], the [[Minister of Housing and Local Government]], performed the ceremony in September 1957. The total cost of the project was \u00a36 million, and when full, the reservoir can hold {{convert|26075|Ml|e6impgal|order=flip}}. If supplies around {{convert|150|Ml|e6impgal|order=flip}} or treated water per day, although the maximum throughput of the works is {{convert|225|Ml|e6impgal|order=flip}} per day. Water levels fluctuate seasonally, and during the winter months, up to {{convert|240|Ml|e6impgal|order=flip}} per day are pumped into the reservoir via the Langford pipeline.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.eswater.co.uk/media-centre/3190_3147.aspx |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180111110227/https://www.eswater.co.uk/media-centre/3190_3147.aspx |archivedate=11 January 2018 |url-status=live |title=Pure Gold |publisher=Essex and Suffolk Water |date=9 August 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn order to meet the rising demands for water faced by both companies, the next major project was the Ely-Ouse to Essex Transfer Scheme. Surplus water in the [[River Great Ouse]], which would otherwise flow into the sea, was to be diverted via a series of channels, tunnels and pipelines to augment supplies to the Abberton and Hanningfield reservoirs. At the northern end, the Cut Off Channel carries the headwaters of the [[River Lark]], the [[River Little Ouse]] and the [[River Wissey]] to the Great Ouse at Denver Sluice, when those rivers are in flood. An intake was constructed at Blackdyke, close to the Little Ouse, and a tunnel carries the water to a pumping station at [[Kennett, Cambridgeshire|Kennett]]. From there a {{convert|1.83|m|ft|order=flip|adj=on}} pipeline carries the water to [[Kirtling|Kirtling Green]] Outfall, where it enters Kirtling Brook, a tributary of the River Stour. Further down the Stour, some of the water is removed from the river by [[Wixoe]] pumping station. A {{convert|1.68|m|ft|order=flip|adj=on}} diameter pipeline carries it to the [[Great Sampford]] outfall, where it is discharged into the River Pant, the name of the upper reaches of the River Blackwater.{{sfn |ESW |2006 |p=22}} Construction of the scheme was completed in 1971.{{sfn |Barty-King |1992 |p=189}}\n\n===Suffolk Water plc===\nThe Great Yarmouth Waterworks Company was set up in 1853, authorised by the Great Yarmouth Waterworks Act of that year. They built a waterworks at [[Trinity Broads|Ormesby Broad]], from where water flowed by gravity into Great Yarmouth. Two steam engines raised the water up to some filter beds.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://greatyarmouthhistory.com/perlustration/The%20Guided%20Tour.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150227123504/http://greatyarmouthhistory.com/perlustration/The%20Guided%20Tour.htm |archivedate=27 February 2015 |title=The Guided Tour |publisher=Great Yarmouth History |accessdate=27 February 2015}}</ref> The construction of the distribution network of pipes through the town was completed in 1855, when the Ormesby Waterworks was opened.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gtyarmouth.co.uk/bygones/crisp/html/crisp2.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312034450/http://www.gtyarmouth.co.uk/bygones/crisp/html/crisp2.htm |archivedate=12 March 2017 |url-status=live |title=Chronological Retrospect 1800 - 1877 |first=William |last=Finch-Crisp |publisher=Great Yarmouth History |accessdate=27 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nPublic water supply in Lowestoft also began in 1853,<ref>The Lowestoft Water, Gas and Market Act 1853 (c. xviii)</ref> with the creation of the Lowestoft Water, Gas and Market Company. They retained this name until 1897, when they became the Lowestoft Water and Gas Company.<ref>The Lowestoft Water and Gas Act 1897 (c. cx)</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/rd/a7d42d15-6c1a-4ed3-9688-4fba6d45aaeb |title=Lowestoft Water and Gas Company |publisher=The National Archives |accessdate=27 February 2015}}</ref> The company had an authorised capital of \u00a325,000, and bought the gas works for \u00a35,000. Water was supplied to a tower at Kirkley from a well at Middle West Field,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lucasbrothers.co.uk/?year=1850 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140622220227/http://www.lucasbrothers.co.uk/?year=1850 |archivedate=22 June 2014 |url-status=live |title=Messrs Lucas Brothers |accessdate=27 February 2015}}</ref> and subsequently from a lake at Bunkers Hill, [[Lound, Suffolk|Lound]]. From there it was pumped through a {{convert|5|mi|km|adj=on}} pipeline to a covered reservoir located to the north of the town.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://forebears.co.uk/england/suffolk/lowestoft |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180111052654/http://forebears.co.uk/england/suffolk/lowestoft |archivedate=11 January 2018 |url-status=live |title=Historical Description |publisher=Forebears |accessdate=27 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nBoth the company and the Great Yarmouth company were finding that the supplies were inadequate for the populations of the two towns, particularly are there was a large seasonal tourist trade, and in 1906, they attempted to get authorisation for extracting water from the [[River Bure]]. The bill faced a rough passage through Parliament, as there were objections to parts of it from [[Norfolk County Council]], the Great Yarmouth Corporation, the Great Yarmouth Court Commissioners, the London Drainage Commissioners, the [[Ecclesiastical Commissioners]] for England, and some private individuals. The chief concerns were that removing water from the Bure would impede navigation, and that the quality of the water would be poor, and unfit to supply as drinking water.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/lords/1906/mar/13/great-yarmouth-waterworks-and-lowestoft |title=Great Yarmouth Waterworks and Lowestoft Water and Gas Bill |publisher=Hansard |accessdate=27 February 2015}}</ref> However, the bill eventually became the Great Yarmouth Waterworks and Lowestoft Water and Gas Act 1907.<ref>The Great Yarmouth Water-works and Lowestoft Water and Gas Act 1907 (c. lxxxiv)</ref><ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/28044/page/5117/data.pdf |title=Westminster, July 26, 1907 |work=The London Gazette |date=26 July 1907 |issue=28044}}</ref>\n\nThe two companies amalgamated in 1962 to become the East Anglian Water Company. The merger was sanctioned by the East Anglian Water Order 1962,<ref>The East Anglian Water Order 1961 S.I. 1961/2291</ref> using the powers of the [[Water Act 1945]]. By this time the Lowestoft Water and Gas Company was known as the Lowestoft Water Company, as all gas companies had been [[Gas Act 1948|nationalised in 1948]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.acraew.org.uk/sites/default/files/uploads/Norfolk/THE%20STAITHE%20-%20ORMESBY%20ST%20MICHAEL%20-%20GREAT%20YARMOUTH%20DISTRICT%20NO.CL.128.pdf |title=Hearing of the Commons Registration Act 1965 |publisher=Association of Commons Registration Authorities |accessdate=27 February 2015}}</ref> A further change of name occurred on 18 January 1991, when it became Suffolk Water plc, and the new company was taken over by Essex Water on 8 April 1994, to become Essex and Suffolk Water. Both were owned by the French company {{ill|Lyonnaise des Eaux-Dumez|fr|Lyonnaise des eaux}} at the time.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.suffolkarchives.co.uk/collections/getrecord/GB175_1176_2_2_19_602 |title=Search results in the Suffolk Record Office collections |publisher=Suffolk County Council |accessdate=27 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Essex and Suffolk Water===\nIn order to provide improved supplies to Great Yarmouth, the company bought most of the [[Trinity Broads]] in 1995. These are isolated from the [[River Bure]] by a narrow channel, and have been further protected by the installation of a sluice gate. They were designated as a [[Site of Special Scientific Interest]] in 1998.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eswater.co.uk/TrinityBroads.aspx |publisher=Essex and Suffolk Water |title=Trinity Broads |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101003104230/http://www.eswater.co.uk/TrinityBroads.aspx |archivedate=3 October 2010 |accessdate=6 March 2015}}</ref> Osmesby Works is situated by the side of Ormesby Broad, and can treat water from the broads. A second source of water is pumped some {{convert|18|mi|km}} from the River Bure to the works. Parts of the works date from the 1930s, and others from the 1950s, but a major upgrade was completed in 2005, to enhance the treatment of water from the broads, which is affected by [[algal bloom]] for around a quarter of each year.{{sfn |Walker |2004 |p=233}}  \n\nIn order to meet long term supply requirements, the company looked at several options, and in 1997 settled on expanding the capacity of Abberton Reservoir. After ten years of design work and a lengthy tendering process, work began in January 2010 on a project costed at \u00a3150 million, to increase the capacity of the reservoir by 58 per cent, and to upgrade the capacity of the Ely-Ouse Essex Transfer Scheme.{{sfn |Wilson |2012 |p=240}} The clay core of the main dam was raised by {{convert|9.5|ft|m}}, to allow the water level to be raised by {{convert|10.5|ft|m}}, increasing the surface area of the reservoir from {{convert|1.8|sqmi|km2}} to {{convert|2.5|sqmi|km2}}.{{sfn |Wilson |2012 |p=241}} The original pumping station which pumped water to Layer de la Haye treatment works would have been submerged by the new water levels, and so had to be demolished and rebuilt at a higher level. In order to keep the system operational while this was being done, a temporary pumping station was built on the shore of the reservoir.{{sfn |Wilson |2012 |p=242}} The new station can deliver {{convert|231|Ml|e6impgal|order=flip}} of raw water per day to the works.{{sfn |Wilson |2012 |p=241}} Other enhancements at the reservoir site included the construction of a new visitor centre for the [[Essex Wildlife Trust]], and work on the B1026 causeway, which crossed the reservoir at a height where it would be below the level of the new water surface.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.eswater.co.uk/your-home/your-services/abberton-enhancement.aspx |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160314164248/https://www.eswater.co.uk/your-home/your-services/abberton-enhancement.aspx |archivedate=14 March 2016 |title=Reservoir enhancement |publisher=Essex and Suffolk Water |accessdate=6 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nWith the capacity of the reservoir increased from {{convert|26000|to|41000|Ml|e6impgal|order=flip}}, two new pipelines were constructed, to improve the transfer of water from the Ouse.{{sfn |Jenkins |2013 |p=253}} The Ely Ouse to Essex Transfer Scheme was licensed to allow {{convert|455|Ml|e6impgal|order=flip}} per day to be transferred, but the pumps at the Kennett pumping station could not deliver this volume, and the maximum permitted discharge into the river at Kirtling Green was {{convert|344|Ml|e6impgal|order=flip}} per day. As part of the upgrade, three additional pumps were installed at Kennett.{{sfn |Jenkins |2013 |p=255}} Around {{convert|9.6|mi|km}} of new underground pipeline was constructed from Kirtling Green in Suffolk, along the banks of the Stour to Wixoe, where the water discharges into the river. Most is {{convert|4|ft|m|adj=on}} in diameter, but this reduces to {{convert|3.3|ft|m}} for the final {{convert|2.1|mi|km}}, where the gradient is steeper.{{sfn |Jenkins |2013 |p=253}} It can deliver an additional {{convert|145|Ml|e6impgal|order=flip}} per day into the river system.{{sfn |Jenkins |2013 |p=255}} Further down the river, a new pumping station was constructed at Wormingford, to remove the water from the river and pump it to Abberton. The pumping station pumps the water for approximately {{convert|1.2|mi|km|0}} to a break tank, from where it can flow by gravity to the reservoir. Most of the two pipelines were installed using [[cut and cover]] techniques, but the southern pipeline passes under the [[River Colne, Essex|River Colne]] and beneath the [[A12 road (England)|A12 road]] and the [[Great Eastern Main Line|East Coast railway]] to the west of [[Colchester]]. Twin shafts, {{convert|23|ft|m|0}} in diameter and {{convert|66|ft|m}} deep were excavated, and {{convert|490|ft|m}} of {{convert|5|ft|m|adj=on}} diameter bored tunnel passed under both the road and the railway. The pipeline was then laid through the tunnel and grouted in.{{sfn |Jenkins |2013 |pp=253-254}} The entire project was completed in 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.eswater.co.uk/_assets/documents/Timescales.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402125947/https://www.eswater.co.uk/_assets/documents/Timescales.pdf |archivedate=2 April 2015 |url-status=live|title=Timescales |publisher=Essex and Suffolk Water |accessdate=6 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Supply area==\nThe company supplies water to an area of {{convert|2861|sqkm|sqmi|order=flip}} in southeast Norfolk, east Suffolk, Essex and the London boroughs of [[London Borough of Barking and Dagenham|Barking and Dagenham]], [[London Borough of Havering|Havering]] and [[London Borough of Redbridge|Redbridge]] in Greater London. The total population served is 1.8 million, through over 735,000 domestic connections and over 47,000 non-household connections.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.eswater.co.uk/media-centre/3190_2567.aspx |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150222151924/https://www.eswater.co.uk/media-centre/3190_2567.aspx |archivedate=22 February 2015 |url-status=live |title=Winning the right to bid for \u00a31.5 billion worth of work |publisher=Essex and Suffolk Water |accessdate=22 February 2015}}</ref> Essex and Suffolk is a 'water only' supplier, with sewerage services supplied by [[Anglian Water]] (Essex, Norfolk, Suffolk and part of Upminster) and [[Thames Water]] (Greater London and part of Brentwood).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eswater.co.uk/business/btariffs-and-charges.aspx |title=Unmetered charges |publisher=Essex and Suffolk Water |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130103213649/http://www.eswater.co.uk/business/btariffs-and-charges.aspx |archivedate=3 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{Refbegin}}\n*{{cite book\n  |first=Hugh |last=Barty-King\n  |title=Water The Book\n  |publisher=Quiller Press\n  |year=1992\n  |isbn=978-1-870948-74-6\n  |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite web\n  |url=http://www.museumofpower.org.uk/History.html\n  |first1=Patrick |last1=Chaplin\n  |first2=Irene |last2=Allen\n  |title=Station History\n  |publisher=Museum of Power, Langford\n  |year=2011\n  |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite web\n  |url=http://www.eswater.co.uk/_assets/documents/Abberton_History_Brochure.pdf\n  |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305145713/https://www.eswater.co.uk/_assets/documents/Abberton_History_Brochure.pdf\n  |archivedate=5 March 2015 |url-status=live\n  |last=ESW\n  |title=Abberton Reservoir Expansion Project\n  |publisher=Essex and Suffolk Water \n  |year=2006\n  |accessdate=20 February 2015\n  |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite web\n  |url=http://www.waterprojectsonline.com/case_studies/2013/E&S_Abberton_Pipeline_2013.pdf\n  |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304061419/http://www.waterprojectsonline.com/case_studies/2013/E%26S_Abberton_Pipeline_2013.pdf\n  |archivedate=4 March 2016\n  |url-status=live\n  |first=Jim\n  |last=Jenkins\n  |title=Abberton Pipelines Project\n  |publisher=Water Projects Online\n  |year=2013\n  |ref=harv\n  |access-date=11 August 2019\n  }}\n*{{cite web\n  |url=http://www.ofwat.gov.uk/publications/commissioned/rpt_com_devwatindust270106.pdf\n  |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150716224258/http://www.ofwat.gov.uk/publications/commissioned/rpt_com_devwatindust270106.pdf\n  |archivedate=16 July 2015\n  |last=Ofwat\n  |title=The Development of the Water Industry in England and Wales\n  |year=2006\n  |publisher=[[OFWAT]]\n  |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book\n  |url=http://www.itsaboutmaldon.co.uk/langford_pumping_station/\n  |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171024124510/http://www.itsaboutmaldon.co.uk/langford_pumping_station/\n  |archivedate=24 October 2017\n  |url-status=live\n  |last=SWC\n  |title=An illustrated description of the works at Langford, Maldon\n  |publisher=Southend Waterworks Company\n  |