{"title_page": "Herbert Knowles", "text_new": "'''Herbert Knowles''' (1798\u20131817) was an [[England|English]] [[poet]].\n\nKnowles was the author of the well-known ''[[Stanzas written in Richmond Churchyard]]'', which gave promise of future excellence.  However, he died a few weeks after he had been enabled, through the help of [[Robert Southey]] to whom he had sent some of his poems, to go to the [[University of Cambridge]].\n\n{{A Short Biographical Dictionary of English Literature}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{DNB Cite|wstitle=Knowles, Herbert}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Knowles, Herbert}}\n[[Category:1798 births]]\n[[Category:1817 deaths]]\n[[Category:English male poets]]\n[[Category:19th-century English poets]]\n[[Category:19th-century British male writers]]\n\n\n{{England-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Herbert Knowles''' (1798\u20131817) was an [[England|English]] [[poet]].\n\nKnowles was the author of the well-known ''[[Stanzas written in Richmond Churchyard]]'', which gave promise of future excellence.  However, he died a few weeks after he had been enabled, through the help of [[Robert Southey]] to whom he had sent some of his poems, to go to the [[University of Cambridge]].\n\n{{A Short Biographical Dictionary of English Literature}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{DNB Cite|wstitle=Knowles, Herbert}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Knowles, Herbert}}\n[[Category:1798 births]]\n[[Category:1817 deaths]]\n[[Category:English male poets]]\n[[Category:19th-century English poets]]\n[[Category:19th-century British male writers]]\n\n\n{{England-writer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Herbert_Knowles"}
{"title_page": "Ted Smith (footballer, born 1914)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2016}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|name = Ted Smith\n|fullname = John Edward Smith\n|birth_date = {{birth date|1914|9|3|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Grays, Essex|Grays]], England\n|death_date = {{death year and age|1989|1914}}\n|death_place = [[Lisbon]], Portugal\n|position = [[Defender (Association football)|Full back]]\n|years1 = 1935\u20131948\n|clubs1 = [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]]\n|caps1 = 143<ref name=caps />\n|goals1 = 1\n|manageryears1 = 1948\u20131952 \n|managerclubs1 = [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]]\n|manageryears2 = 1971\u20131973 \n|managerclubs2 = [[Atl\u00e9tico Clube de Portugal|Atletico]]\n}}\n'''John Edward Smith''' (3 September 1914 \u2013 1989), commonly known as '''Ted Smith''', was an English [[association football|footballer]] who played as [[Defender (Association football)|full back]], and a coach.\n\nSmith represented [[Millwall F.C.]] in the late 1930s, he then coached [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]] from 1948 to 1952  guiding them to their first international trophy.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ted Smith - a true pioneer of football and an inspiration|url=http://themarpleleaf.blogspot.pt/2012/08/ted-smith-true-pioneer-of-football-and.html|work=The Marple Leaf|date=25 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nBorn in [[Grays, Essex|Grays]], in the [[Essex]] county, Smith football career started at [[Millwall F.C.]] in 1935, as the ''Lions'' were on [[Football League Third Division South|Third Division]]. He was part of the squad that eliminated (2\u20130) [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] on the quarter-finals of the [[1936\u201337 FA Cup]], on 6 March 1937, which would be known as one of the historic ''giant-killings'' in the FA Cup.<ref>{{cite web|title=All time greatest F A cup giant killings  Number 30  Millwall 2-0 Manchester City|url=http://www.freewebs.com/captainbeecher/1937millwall.htm|website=freewebs.com|accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref> In the next season, Smith helped the club get promoted to the [[Football League Second Division|second tier]], playing just one season before the War interruption. He competed a further three years, retiring in 1948, age 33, after amassing over 140 league caps.<ref name=caps>{{cite web|title=Ted Smith Profile|url=http://www.neilbrown.newcastlefans.com/player8/tedsmith.html|website=neilbrown.newcastlefans.com|accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe immediately started a managerial career, arriving at [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]] in 1948. The club last league title was in [[1944-45 Primeira Liga|1944\u201345]], and [[Sporting CP]] was in the most successful period of their history, winning seven of the eight championships contested from the 1946\u201347 season to the 1953\u201354 season, losing only in the 1949\u201350 season to Smith's Benfica. This was the age of the Cinco Violinos (\"Five Violins\").\n\nAdding up to the [[1949-50 Primeira Liga|league title]], Smith biggest success, was conquering, the [[Latin Cup]], the predecessor of [[UEFA Champions League]], contested by [[Romance-speaking Europe|Latin European]] nations of France, Italy, Spain and Portugal, in a tournament organized at the end of the season, defeating [[FC Girondins de Bordeaux|Bordeaux]] at [[Est\u00e1dio Nacional]] on 18 June 1950.<ref>{{cite web|title=Latin Cup winners|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesl/latin.html}}</ref>\n\nAfter bagging his second [[Ta\u00e7a de Portugal]] in his third year in charge, his fourth year was more irregular.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sabotagetimes.com/reportage/the-englishman-who-transformed-benfica-the-strange-tale-of-ted-smith/ |title=TheEnglishman Who Transformed Benfica: My Granddad's Mate Ted Smith |date=4 January 2014 |work=Sabotage Times|accessdate=8 January 2014}}</ref> In December, Smith, resigned for personal problems, changed his mind in March and returned, but only for a month, leaving again in April. His successor, [[C\u00e2ndido Tavares]] won the Ta\u00e7a de Portugal preventing a trophyless season.<ref name=SLB>{{cite book|title=Almanaque do Benfica|year=2012|publisher=Lua de Papel|location=Portugal|isbn=978-989-23-2087-8|pages=214\u2013238}}</ref>\n\nAfter Benfica, Smith managed [[Workington A.F.C.]] for one season, and had a short spell at [[Atl\u00e9tico Clube de Portugal|Atletico]] in the early 1970s.\n\n==Managerial statistics==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Team\n!rowspan=\"2\"|From\n!rowspan=\"2\"|To\n!colspan=\"8\"|Record\n|-\n!G!!W!!D!!L!!Win %\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]]<ref name=SLB />\n|align=\"left\"|1 July 1948\n|align=\"left\"|6 April 1952\n| 109 || 73 || 18 || 18 || {{#expr: 73/109 * 100 round 2}} \n|}\n\n==Honours==\n;Benfica<ref name=SLB />\n*[[Latin Cup]]: 1949\u201350\n*[[Primeira Liga]]: [[1949\u201350 Primeira Divis\u00e3o|1949\u201350]] \n*[[Ta\u00e7a de Portugal]]: 1948\u201349; 1950\u201351\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{S.L. Benfica managers}}\n{{Workington A.F.C. managers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, Ted}}\n[[Category:1914 births]]\n[[Category:1989 deaths]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Millwall F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English football managers]]\n[[Category:S.L. Benfica managers]]\n[[Category:Workington A.F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Association football fullbacks]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2016}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|name = Ted Smith\n|fullname = John Edward Smith\n|birth_date = {{birth date|1914|9|3|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Grays]], England\n|death_date = {{death year and age|1989|1914}}\n|death_place = [[Lisbon]], Portugal\n|position = [[Defender (Association football)|Full back]]\n|years1 = 1935\u20131948\n|clubs1 = [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]]\n|caps1 = 143<ref name=caps />\n|goals1 = 1\n|manageryears1 = 1948\u20131952 \n|managerclubs1 = [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]]\n|manageryears2 = 1971\u20131973 \n|managerclubs2 = [[Atl\u00e9tico Clube de Portugal|Atletico]]\n}}\n'''John Edward Smith''' (3 September 1914 \u2013 1989), commonly known as '''Ted Smith''', was an English [[association football|footballer]] who played as [[Defender (Association football)|full back]], and a coach.\n\nSmith represented [[Millwall F.C.]] in the late 1930s, he then coached [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]] from 1948 to 1952  guiding them to their first international trophy.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ted Smith - a true pioneer of football and an inspiration|url=http://themarpleleaf.blogspot.pt/2012/08/ted-smith-true-pioneer-of-football-and.html|work=The Marple Leaf|date=25 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nBorn in [[Grays]], in the [[Essex]] county, Smith football career started at [[Millwall F.C.]] in 1935, as the ''Lions'' were on [[Football League Third Division South|Third Division]]. He was part of the squad that eliminated (2\u20130) [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] on the quarter-finals of the [[1936\u201337 FA Cup]], on 6 March 1937, which would be known as one of the historic ''giant-killings'' in the FA Cup.<ref>{{cite web|title=All time greatest F A cup giant killings  Number 30  Millwall 2-0 Manchester City|url=http://www.freewebs.com/captainbeecher/1937millwall.htm|website=freewebs.com|accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref> In the next season, Smith helped the club get promoted to the [[Football League Second Division|second tier]], playing just one season before the War interruption. He competed a further three years, retiring in 1948, age 33, after amassing over 140 league caps.<ref name=caps>{{cite web|title=Ted Smith Profile|url=http://www.neilbrown.newcastlefans.com/player8/tedsmith.html|website=neilbrown.newcastlefans.com|accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe immediately started a managerial career, arriving at [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]] in 1948. The club last league title was in [[1944-45 Primeira Liga|1944\u201345]], and [[Sporting CP]] was in the most successful period of their history, winning seven of the