{"title_page": "Totomycin", "text_new": "{{Drugbox\n| Verifiedfields = changed\n| Watchedfields = changed\n| verifiedrevid = 441941911\n| IUPAC_name = (''E'')-''N''-[(3aS,4R,5R,6S,7R,7aR)-4,6,7-Trihydroxy-3a,4,5,6,7,7a-hexahydro-1,3-benzodioxol-5-yl]-3-[4-[(2''S'',3''S'',4''S'',5''S'')-5-acetyl-3,4-dihydroxyoxolan-2-yl]oxy-3-hydroxyphenyl]-2-methylprop-2-enamide\n| image = Hygromycin A Molecular Structure.svg\n| width = 220\n\n<!--Clinical data-->\n| tradename =  \n| Drugs.com = \n\n<!--Identifiers-->\n| CAS_number_Ref = {{cascite|correct|??}}\n| CAS_number = 6379-56-2\n| UNII_Ref = {{fdacite|correct|FDA}}\n| UNII = 3YJY415DDI\n| ATC_prefix = none\n| PubChem = 6433481\n| DrugBank_Ref = {{drugbankcite|correct|drugbank}}\n| DrugBank =  \n| ChemSpiderID_Ref = {{chemspidercite|correct|chemspider}}\n| ChemSpiderID = 4938630\n| ChEMBL_Ref = {{ebicite|changed|EBI}}\n| ChEMBL = \n\n<!--Chemical data-->\n| C=23 | H=29 | N=1 | O=12 \n| molecular_weight = 511.475 g/mol\n| smiles = C/C(=C\\C1=CC(=C(C=C1)O[C@H]2[C@H]([C@@H]([C@H](O2)C(=O)C)O)O)O)/C(=O)N[C@@H]3[C@@H]([C@H]([C@@H]4[C@H]([C@@H]3O)OCO4)O)O\n| StdInChI_Ref = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}}\n| StdInChI=1S/C23H29NO12/c1-8(22(32)24-13-14(27)16(29)21-20(15(13)28)33-7-34-21)5-10-3-4-12(11(26)6-10)35-23-18(31)17(30)19(36-23)9(2)25/h3-6,13-21,23,26-31H,7H2,1-2H3,(H,24,32)/b8-5+/t13-,14+,15-,16-,17+,18+,19-,20+,21-,23-/m1/s1\n| StdInChIKey_Ref = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}}\n| StdInChIKey = YQYJSBFKSSDGFO-IIHALWDASA-N\n| synonyms = Hygromycin A, Homomycin\n| melting_point     = 110\n| melting_high      = 112\n| melting_notes     = (decomp.)\n}}\n\n'''Totomycin''' (also known as '''hygromycin A''') is an [[aminoglycoside]] [[antibiotic]] produced by ''[[Streptomyces hygroscopicus]]'', first described in the 1950s. The bacteria source is similar to that of [[hygromycin B]] from which the name of the compound was derived. \n\n==History==\nHygromycin A was discovered in a soil sample from a forest near Indianapolis, Indiana in 1953 by Waksman and Henrici.<ref> R.L. Mann et al., Antibiot. Chemother. 3, 1279 (1953)</ref> Identification and structure of totomycin wasn't determined until 1957.\n\n==Antibiotic activity==\nThe strongest antibiotic activity of totomycin is against ''[[Staphylococcus haemolyticus]]'' in which growth was inhibited by concentrations of 2&nbsp;\u00b5g/mL. Other gram-positive and gram-negative sensitive to totomycin are inhibited by concentrations from 16 to 31&nbsp;\u00b5g/mL.<ref> A new antibiotic, Totomycin. Brit. Pat., 758276 (1956) </ref>\n\n==Total synthesis==\nTotomycin has been a successful target in [[total synthesis]] since 1989.<ref> N. Chida et al., Chem. Commun. 1989, 436. </ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Aminoglycoside antibiotics]]\n", "text_old": "{{Drugbox\n| Verifiedfields = changed\n| Watchedfields = changed\n| verifiedrevid = 441941911\n| IUPAC_name = (''E'')-''N''-[(3aS,4R,5R,6S,7R,7aR)-4,6,7-Trihydroxy-3a,4,5,6,7,7a-hexahydro-1,3-benzodioxol-5-yl]-3-[4-[(2''S'',3''S'',4''S'',5''S'')-5-acetyl-3,4-dihydroxyoxolan-2-yl]oxy-3-hydroxyphenyl]-2-methylprop-2-enamide\n| image = Hygromycin A Molecular Structure.svg\n| width = 220\n\n<!--Clinical data-->\n| tradename =  \n| Drugs.com = \n\n<!--Identifiers-->\n| CAS_number_Ref = {{cascite|correct|??}}\n| CAS_number = 6379-56-2\n| ATC_prefix = none\n| PubChem = 6433481\n| DrugBank_Ref = {{drugbankcite|correct|drugbank}}\n| DrugBank =  \n| ChemSpiderID_Ref = {{chemspidercite|correct|chemspider}}\n| ChemSpiderID = 4938630\n| ChEMBL_Ref = {{ebicite|changed|EBI}}\n| ChEMBL = \n\n<!--Chemical data-->\n| C=23 | H=29 | N=1 | O=12 \n| molecular_weight = 511.475 g/mol\n| smiles = C/C(=C\\C1=CC(=C(C=C1)O[C@H]2[C@H]([C@@H]([C@H](O2)C(=O)C)O)O)O)/C(=O)N[C@@H]3[C@@H]([C@H]([C@@H]4[C@H]([C@@H]3O)OCO4)O)O\n| StdInChI_Ref = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}}\n| StdInChI=1S/C23H29NO12/c1-8(22(32)24-13-14(27)16(29)21-20(15(13)28)33-7-34-21)5-10-3-4-12(11(26)6-10)35-23-18(31)17(30)19(36-23)9(2)25/h3-6,13-21,23,26-31H,7H2,1-2H3,(H,24,32)/b8-5+/t13-,14+,15-,16-,17+,18+,19-,20+,21-,23-/m1/s1\n| StdInChIKey_Ref = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}}\n| StdInChIKey = YQYJSBFKSSDGFO-IIHALWDASA-N\n| synonyms = Hygromycin A, Homomycin\n| melting_point     = 110\n| melting_high      = 112\n| melting_notes     = (decomp.)\n}}\n\n'''Totomycin''' (also known as '''hygromycin A''') is an [[aminoglycoside]] [[antibiotic]] produced by ''[[Streptomyces hygroscopicus]]'', first described in the 1950s. The bacteria source is similar to that of [[hygromycin B]] from which the name of the compound was derived. \n\n==History==\nHygromycin A was discovered in a soil sample from a forest near Indianapolis, Indiana in 1953 by Waksman and Henrici.<ref> R.L. Mann et al., Antibiot. Chemother. 3, 1279 (1953)</ref> Identification and structure of totomycin wasn't determined until 1957.\n\n==Antibiotic activity==\nThe strongest antibiotic activity of totomycin is against ''[[Staphylococcus haemolyticus]]'' in which growth was inhibited by concentrations of 2&nbsp;\u00b5g/mL. Other gram-positive and gram-negative sensitive to totomycin are inhibited by concentrations from 16 to 31&nbsp;\u00b5g/mL.<ref> A new antibiotic, Totomycin. Brit. Pat., 758276 (1956) </ref>\n\n==Total synthesis==\nTotomycin has been a successful target in [[total synthesis]] since 1989.<ref> N. Chida et al., Chem. Commun. 1989, 436. </ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Aminoglycoside antibiotics]]\n", "name_user": "Fswitzer4", "label": "safe", "comment": "added FDA UNII to drug box", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Totomycin"}
{"title_page": "Saritha", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Saritha\n| birth_place        = Munipalle, [[Guntur district]], [[Andhra Pradesh]], [[India]]     \n| spouse             =  [[Mukesh (actor)|Mukesh]] (m. 1988-2011 \n| residence          = [[Dubai]], [[United Arab Emirates]]\n| occupation         = [[Film actress]], [[Dubbing (filmmaking)|dubbing artist]]\n| years_active       = 1978\u20131989; 2001-2004; 2013-present 2014\n}}\n\n'''Saritha''' is a [[South India]]n actress who has acted in more than 250 films in [[Tamil language|Tamil]], [[Malayalam language|Malayalam]], [[Kannada language|Kannada]] and [[Telugu language|Telugu]] languages. She was one of the popular and critically acclaimed lead actresses during the 1980s. She also appeared in a television serial, ''Selvi''. She is also credited as a [[Dubbing (filmmaking)|dubbing artist]]. She has dubbed her voice for [[Tamil cinema|Tamil]], [[Kannada]], [[Malayalam]] and [[Telugu language|Telugu]] movies for actresses like [[Nagma]], [[Vijayashanti]], [[Tabu (actress)|Tabu]], [[Sushmita Sen]], [[Ramya Krishnan]] and [[Soundarya]] in 1990s.\n\nShe is a recipient of several state awards from Tamil, Telugu and Kannada, six [[Filmfare Awards]] and six [[Nandi Awards]] including a [[Nandi Special Jury Award|Special Jury Award]] for the film ''kannan'' Saritha received [[Tamil Nadu State Film Awards]] four times, [[Karnataka State Film Awards]] once and many Film fans association awards.\n\n==Career==\nSaritha made her acting debut through ''[[Maro Charitra]]'', a [[Telugu language|Telugu]] film directed by [[K. Balachander]]. The movie dealt with [[cross-cultural]] romance, where she acted opposite [[Kamal Haasan]] as a Telugu-speaking girl. She received more offers in Tamil films, mostly directed by Balachander. Some of her films are ''[[Thappu Thalangal]]'', ''[[Idi Katha Kaadu]]'', ''[[Vandichakkaram]]'', ''[[Netrikan]]'', ''[[Agni Sakshi (1982 film)|Agni Sakshi]]'', ''[[Puthukavithai]]'', ''[[Kalyana Agathigal]]'' and ''[[Achamillai Achamillai]]''. Her performance in ''Vandichakkaram'' (1980) and ''[[Achamillai Achamillai]]'' (1984) won her the [[Filmfare Award for Best Actress \u2013 Tamil|Filmfare Best Tamil Actress]] awards. She also played guest roles as herself in ''[[47 Natkal]]'' and its Telugu remake, directed by Balachander.<ref>[http://www.hinduonnet.com/thehindu/mp/2005/04/27/stories/2005042700340100.htm Second time also lucky] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090306023912/http://www.hinduonnet.com/thehindu/mp/2005/04/27/stories/2005042700340100.htm |date=6 March 2009 }}. Hinduonnet.com (27 April 2005). Retrieved on 24 August 2013.</ref>\n\nShe acted in many popular [[Kannada]] movies with famous Kannada actor [[Rajkumar (actor)|Dr.Rajkumar]] like ''[[Hosa Belaku]]'', ''[[Keralida Simha]]'', ''[[Bhakta Prahlada (1983 film)|Bhakta Prahlada]]'', ''[[Chalisuva Modagalu]]'' and ''[[Kaamana Billu]]''. Her other popular Kannada movies include ''[[Eradu Rekhegalu]]'', ''Sankranthi'' and ''[[Malaya Marutha]]''.\n\nShe had her head [[tonsure]]d for the cancer-affected role in ''Sujatha'' in 1980 and gained several pounds to play the psychotic role in the 2005 film ''[[Julie Ganapathi]]''. Neither of these films were successful. She also won a [[Nandi Special Jury Award]] for her performance as \"Aandaalu\" in the movie ''[[Arjun (2004 film)|Arjun]]'' in 2004.\n\nSaritha also worked as a [[Voice acting|voice actor]] in Kannada, Telugu and Tamil films. She has lent her voice to other actresses, including [[Madhavi (actress)|Madhavi]], [[Soundarya]], [[Ramya Krishnan]], [[Nagma]], [[Vijayashanti]], [[Simran]], [[Tabu (actress)|Tabu]], [[Sushmita Sen]], Roja, Suhasini, Radha, Radhika and Aarthi Agarwal. She won the [[Nandi Award for Best Female Dubbing Artist]] for her voice to [[Soundarya]] in ''[[Ammoru]]'', ''Maa Ayana Bangaram'' (1997) and  ''[[Anthapuram (1998 film)|Anthapuram]]'' (1999).\n\n==Personal life==\nSaritha was born in {{not a typo|Munipalle}}, [[Guntur district]], India. She married twice. Her first marriage was with Telugu actor Venkata Subbaih in 1975 and they divorced in 1976. Her second marriage was with Malayalam actor [[Mukesh (actor)|Mukesh]] on 2 September 1988 and has two sons Shravan and Tejas.  The couple divorced in 2011. Saritha now stays with her son Shravan in Dubai, UAE.<ref>{{cite web |author=mangalam |url=http://www.mangalamvarika.com/index.php/en/home/index/125/28 |title=Mangalam - Varika 3-Feb-2014 |publisher=Mangalamvarika.com |accessdate=17 October 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160319000816/http://www.mangalamvarika.com/index.php/en/home/index/125/28 |archive-date=19 March 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Her sister [[Viji Chandrasekhar]] is also an actress.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/i-can-never-let-kb-down-aarohanam/article7239086.ece |title=I can never let KB down: Aarohanam |publisher=The Hindu |date=23 May 2015 |accessdate=17 October 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201085117/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/i-can-never-let-kb-down-aarohanam/article7239086.ece |archive-date=1 December 2017 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n\n;[[Filmfare Awards South]]\n* 1980 \u2013 [[Filmfare Award for Best Actress \u2013 Tamil|Best Actress \u2013 Tamil]] - ''[[Vandichakkaram]]''\n* 1982 \u2013 [[Filmfare Award for Best Actress \u2013 Kannada|Best Actress \u2013 Kannada]] - ''Hosa Belaku''\n* 1984 \u2013 Best Actress \u2013 Tamil - ''[[Achamillai Achamillai]]''\n* 1985 \u2013 Best Actress \u2013 Kannada - ''[[Mugila Mallige]]''\n* 1986 \u2013 Best Actress \u2013 Kannada - ''Mouna Geethe''\n* 1989 \u2013 Best Actress \u2013 Kannada - ''Sankranthi''\n\n;[[Nandi Awards]]\n* 1982 \u2013 [[Nandi Special Jury Award|Special Jury]] \u2013 Best Actress - ''Kokilamma''\n* 1995 \u2013 [[Nandi Award for Best Female Dubbing Artist|Best Female Dubbing Artist]] - ''Ammoru''\n* 1996 \u2013 Best Female Dubbing Artist - ''Maavichiguru''\n* 1997 \u2013 Best Female Dubbing Artist - ''Maa Ayana Bangaram''\n* 1998 \u2013 Best Female Dubbing Artist - ''[[Anthapuram (1998 film)|Anthapuram]]''\n* 2004 \u2013 Special Jury - ''[[Arjun (2004 film)|Arjun]]''\n\n;[[Tamil Nadu State Film Awards]]\n* Kalaimamani Award from Tamil Nadu State\n* 1979 \u2013 [[Tamil Nadu State Film Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]] - ''Oru Vellaadu Vengaiyagiradhu''\n* 1982 \u2013 Best Actress - ''[[Agni Sakshi (1982 film)|Agni Sakshi]]''\n* 1988 \u2013 Best Actress - ''Poo Pootha Nandavanam''\n* 1995 \u2013 Best Female Dubbing Artist \u2013 ''Amman'' (1995)\n\n;[[Karnataka State Film Awards]]\n* 1989 \u2013 [[Karnataka State Film Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]] - ''Sankranthi''\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Tamil films===\n \n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- style=\"background:#000;\"\n! Year !! Film !! Role || Notes\n|-\n| 1978 || ''[[Thappu Thalangal]]'' || Sarasu || Debut Tamil Film\n|-\n| 1978 || ''[[Aval Appadithan]]'' || Arun's Wife || Guest Appearance\n|-\n| 1979 || Ponnu Oorukku Pudhusu || ||\n|-\n| 1979 || ''[[Chakkalathi]]'' || || Guest Appearance\n|-\n| 1979 || ''[[Nool Veli]]'' || Baby ||\n|-\n| 1980 || ''[[Vandichakkaram]]'' || Vadivu ||\n|-\n| 1980 || ''[[Sujatha (1980 film)|Sujatha]]'' || ||\n|-\n| 1980 || ''[[Oru Velladu Vengaiyagiradhu]]'' || ||\n|-\n| 1980 || ''Thai Pongal'' || ||\n|-\n| 1980 || ''[[Rusi Kanda Poonai]]'' || Savithri ||\n|-\n| 1980 || ''Kuruvikoodu'' || ||\n|-\n| 1980 || ''Panam Penn Paasam'' || ||\n|-\n| 1981 || ''[[Thanneer Thanneer]]'' || Sevanthi ||\n|-\n| 1981 || ''[[Anjatha Nenjangal]]'' || ||\n|-\n| 1981 || ''[[Mouna Geethangal]]'' || Suguna ||\n|-\n| 1981 || ''[[47 Natkal]]'' || ||\n|-\n| 1981 || ''Oruthi Mattum Karaiyinile'' || ||\n|-\n| 1981 || ''[[Netrikkann]]'' || Radha ||\n|-\n| 1981 || ''[[Enga Ooru Kannagi]]'' || ||\n|-\n| 1981 || ''[[Keezh Vaa